text: Edvard Munch s sick child of a highlight from the powerful exhibition of his work until July st at the British Museum The title was actually given to of his works executed over a long period Munch became obsessed with the tragic death of his sister Johanne pictured left from Tuberculosis It is probably her aunt Karen on the right Strong echoes of Picasso s Blue Period of the same time and for the visitor to the Tate Britain the pre raphaelite Too late by William Lindsay Lindus of This also deals with premature death from T B With the surge of Romanticism and the high mortality rate among middle aged adults it became known as the romantic disease bluebadgetouristguide expressionism norway art painting edvardmunch britishmuseum artexhibitions

name: 2019-07-30 06.12.20 2098953191927807663_britishmuseum.jpg
text: La Piedra Rosetta The Rossetta Stone Si estamos frente a este cono de la historia de la humanidad que se encuentra en el Britishmuseum Esta piedra permiti descifrar los jeroglificos ejipcios La piedra fue tallada en el a o a c con un edicto del faraon Ptolomeo V redactado en lenguajes Jeroglifico escritura Dem tica y Griego Antiguo Con el tiempo fue usada como material de construcci n cerca de la desembocadura del Nilo en Rashid o Rosetta Los franceses la encontraron en pero a os despu s luego de la victoria Britanica en Alejandr a los Brit nicos la llevaron a donde est hoy en En Jean Fran ois Champollion logr descifrar el c digo de los jeroglificos Estar parado frente a esta piedra genera una emoci n particular de esas donde parece que el tiempo se detiene y uno quiere que siga detenido ENTEADA GRATUITA Yes we are facing this icon of the history of humanity found in the British Museum This stone allowed to decipher the ejiptian hieroglyphs The stone was carved in the year a c with an edict of Pharaoh Ptolemy V written in languages Hieroglyph Demotic and Ancient Greek writing Over time it was used as building material near the mouth of the Nile in Rashid or Rosetta The French found her in but years later after the British victory in Alexandria the British took her to where she is today in In Jean Fran ois Champollion managed to crack the code of the hieroglyphs Being standing in front of this stone generates a particular emotion of those where it seems that time stands still and one wants it to remain stopped FREE ENTRANCE viajes viajeros fotografia viajerosporelmundo blogger londres london museos museums cultura culture culturas uk travel travelers travellife wonderfulcities seetheworld travelshots holidays vacaciones viajoxmicuenta viajopormicuenta

name: 2019-09-21 17.14.38 2137699652764585994_britishmuseum.jpg
text: The Edge of the Woods c Painted by Charles Courtney Curran Born February Hartford United States Died November New York United States An Impressionist figure genre and landscape painter Charles Curran is known as a prolific artist who created light filled paintings often of young women Curran was born in Hartford Kentucky but in moved to Sandusky Ohio After studying one year at the Cincinnati School of Design he began a distinguished career when he moved to New York City in and enrolled in the National Academy of Design There he studied under Walter Satterlee At age he had his first public exhibition at the Academy and won numerous prizes from that time onward Five years later he received the Academy s Third Hallgarten Prize for A Breezy Day which was considered the most meritorious painting in oil Following his training at the National Academy he became a student at the Art Students League He then studied at the Academie Julian in Paris from to The French artist Jules Bastien Lepage was a source of inspiration for Curran with his paintings of peasants as a common subject matter From to he exhibited regularly at the Pennsylvania Academy In artist Frederick Dellenbaugh invited Curran to Cragsmoor an art center in the Hudson River Valley near Ellenville New York In Curran moved into a house there and established a studio At this time he turned to the themes and Impressionist style that would occupy most of the remaining years of his life young women in bright sunlight His female subjects are often elegantly dressed posed and feminine with uncomplicated and dreamy gazes Curran later included flowered backgrounds in his paintings a theme to last the remainder of his career He occasionally painted portraits and landscapes as well as a series of views of the Imperial Temples of Peking His works can be seen in collections at the Columbus Museum of Art in Ohio the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City the National Gallery of Art in Washington D C and the Toledo Museum of Art in Ohio Fig Details

text: Witty ceramic masks by JonathanBaldock convey a world of emotion CreativeBoomMag looks forward to the artist s upcoming solo exhibition Personae opening at stephenfriedmangallery this Thursday September pm Baldock s work is saturated with humour and wit as well as an uncanny macabre quality that channels the artist s longstanding interest in myth folklore and narratives associated with outsider practices Baldock s upcoming exhibition Personae brings together a new series of ceramic masks that teem with bright colours and outlandish expressions Ripples of clay allude to folds of skin whilst incisions and abstract protuberances reveal physiognomic features such as eyes ears and nostrils Here the artist toys with a cognitive process called pareidolia a psychological phenomenon that causes people to see faces in inanimate objects Whilst some masks mediate universal emotions such as happiness or sadness others merely hint at figuration Personae follows Baldock s solo show at CamdenArtsCentre London earlier this year and precedes a solo exhibition at Kunsthall Stavanger Norway in May Jonathan Baldock Maske I Ceramic x x cm x x in Copyright Jonathan Baldock Courtesy the artist and Stephen Friedman Gallery London britishmuseum creativeboom news contemporaryart mask ceramics camdenartscentre londonexhibition sculpture newexhibition exhibitionopening

text: Found today by a lucky fellow Mudlark this beautiful bosun s whistle really did come out looking like this all thanks to the unique preserving nature of the Thames mud The boatswain s pipe is the modern day descendant of the flutes used by the Ancient Greeks and Romans to convey orders to the oarsmen and galley slaves and the first use of the whistle in the English Navy was during the crusades of the th century The Call or Pipe is named after the Boatswain who was the officer in charge of the rigging and therefore issued more orders than any of the other officers The high pitch of the Boatswain s Call could be be heard above even the worst storms and gales The three rings on the gun of the whistle were introduced to English bosun s whistles in the th century which helps date this one londonmudlark mudlark mudlarking

text: One of my favourite and most important archaeological findings of the th century is the Rosetta Stone BC here shown original spelling being Rashid in Arabic for Rosetta Until the finding in we had no idea what hieroglyphics said for hundreds of years That is for the longest time we had a large chapter missing of the history book of humans Precisely the history of not just Egyptians but of all of us As history is you One must understand that the understanding of history is an understanding of yourself As we are cultural people an amalgamation of all of our experiences has shaped us to who we are now and will be in the future To sum up we now have a one way communication channel with a civilisation and ourselves who have been mute for a millennia permitted to speak of its history magic medicine religion politics and philosophy The top text is Ancient Hieroglyphics Middle is a later cursive version of ancient hieroglyphics called Demotic Bottom is Ancient Greek which is understood well archaeology egyptology hieroglyphics ancientgreek britishmuseum

text: UPCOMING sculptor khaled zaki artfair For the upcoming London edition of the art fair we are delighted to share new bronze works by Khaled Zaki A metaphorical journey Zaki is deeply concerned with the resurrection of his country he zones in on its evolution in the wake of the Arab spring In constant reassessment and refinement of his technique Zaki moved from fluid marble to solid bronze abstract to figurative in a bid to capture and express the feelings dreams and expectations of his society more closely His fluid figures once lying down now stand tall as Egypt finds its strength and pace Dynamic and culturally loaded Zaki s art continues to reveal the complexities of his country as it battles to rebuild itself On his output art writer and academic Anthony Downey suggests We alight upon the twin poles of destruction and rebuilding and how mechanisms of reassembling have been a mainstay not just of sculptural practice but of social and political orders today for better and indeed worse Pictured The Meditator solid bronze Contemporary African Art Fair October somersethouse Stand W BritishMuseum Sufi Bronze AfricanArt Sufi Egypt Cairo tabariartspace art artist artistofinstagram khaledzaki sculpture sculptureart sculptureartist drawing sketch sufism gallery modernart modernartist contemporaryart contemporaryartists abstractart middleeast middleeastart

text: Ni o Comiendo Sand a c Painted by Joaqu n Sorolla y Bastida Born February Valencia Spain Died August Cercedilla Spain Oil on canvas x cm Cuando apenas contaba dos a os de edad fallecieron sus padres v ctimas de una epidemia de c lera Al quedar hu rfanos fueron acogidos su hermana Eugenia y l por su t a Isabel hermana de su madre y su marido de profesi n cerrajero Pasados los a os su t o intent ense arle en vano el oficio de la cerrajer a advirtiendo pronto que su verdadera vocaci n era la pintura Un viaje a Par s en lo puso en contacto con la pintura impresionista lo que supuso una verdadera revoluci n en su estilo Abandon los temas anteriores y comenz a pintar al aire libre dej ndose invadir por la luz y el color del Mediterr neo Son precisamente las obras de colores claros y pincelada vigorosa que reproducen escenas a orillas del mar las que m s se identifican con el arte de Sorolla Sin embargo fue un artista muy activo que realiz tambi n numerosos retratos de personalidades espa olas y algunas obras de denuncia social bajo la influencia de su amigo Blasco Ib ez Su estilo agradable y f cil hizo que recibiera innumerables encargos que le permitieron gozar de una desahogada posici n social Su fama rebas las fronteras espa olas para extenderse por toda Europa y Estados Unidos donde expuso en varias ocasiones De a pint una serie de murales con temas regionales para la Hispanic Society of America de Nueva York En el estilo m s caracter stico de Sorolla el de t cnica y concepci n impresionista destaca la representaci n de la figura humana ni os desnudos mujeres con vestidos vaporosos sobre un fondo de playa o de paisaje donde los reflejos las sombras las transparencias la intensidad de la luz y el color transfiguran la imagen y dan valor a temas en s mismo intrascendentes Algunos cr ticos consideran estas obras un cruce entre los impresionistas franceses y los acuarelistas ingleses Existe una importante colecci n de pintura suya en el text: ancienthistoryart An angel is generally a supernaturalbeing found in various religions andmythologies Abrahamic religionsoften depict angels as benevolent celestial beings who act as intermediaries between God or Heaven and humanity Other roles of angels include protecting and guiding human beings and carrying out tasks on behalf of God Abrahamic religions often organize angels into hierarchies although such rankings may vary between sects in each religion Such angels may receive specific names such as Gabriel or Michael or titles such as seraph or archangel People have also extended the use of the term angel to various notions of spirits or figures found in other religious traditions The theological study of angels is known as angelology Angels expelled from Heaven are referred to as fallen angels as distinct from the heavenly host Melek genellikle e itli dinlerde ve mitolojilerde bulunan do a st bir eydir brahimi dinler genellikle melekleri Tanr ya da Cennet ve insanl k aras nda arac olarak hareket eden yard msever g ksel varl klar olarak tasvir eder Di er melek rolleri aras nda insanlar korumak ve y nlendirmek ve Tanr ad na g revlerini yerine getirmek vard r brahimi dinler genellikle melekleri hiyerar iler halinde d zenler ancak bu t r s ralamalar her dinde mezhepler aras nda de i ebilir Bu t r melekler belirli isimler Gabriel veya Michael gibi veya unvanlar seraph veya ba melek gibi alabilir nsanlar ayr ca melek teriminin kullan m n di er dini geleneklerde bulunan e itli ruh halleri veya fig rler kavramlar na da geni letmi tir Meleklerin teolojik incelemesi melekoloji olarak bilinir Design Crouching Angel Garden Statue ancientarcheology art sanat artwork museitaliani sculpture italia beniculturali escultura statue louvre historic scultura statues tesori italiani beniculturali italy louvremuseum italianart italianartist britishmuseum

text: Myra daki kaya mezarlar Antalya Myra da iki Likya nekropol vard r bunlar tiyatronun zerindeki kayal kta ve onun do usunda nehir nekropol olarak adland r lan b lgede toplanm t r Kaya mezarlar n n o u uzaktan b y k bir ev gibi g r n rler baz lar da tap nak eklindedir Nehir nekropol n n en dikkat eken mezar gezgin Charles Fellows n y l nda kaya mezarlar n g rd zaman hala k rm z sar mavi ve mor renkleri se ebildi ini s yledi i Resimli Mezar d r g n m zde bu renkler g r lemez sadece k rm z ve mavi renklerden izler vard r Bu mezarda di er bir dikkat eken ey ger ek l lerde kabartma eklinde yap lm on bir insan fig r d r Rock tombs in Myra Antalya Turkey There are two Lycian necropolises in Myra which are gathered in the rock above the theater and in the east of the river necropolis Most of the rock tombs appear to be a large house in the distance some are in the form of a temple The most striking tomb of the river necropolis is the pictorial grave of the traveler Charles Fellows who when he saw the rock tombs in was still able to choose red yellow blue and purple colors Nowadays these colors cannot be seen only red and blue color traces Another remarkable thing in this grave is the figure of eleven human figures in the form of reliefs Bizi takip etmeyi unutmay n follow us archeo travel ancient road Contact Pages sevgiiyenerr Photo by baya iyi archeotravel arkeoloji archaeology arqueologia archeologia italianart italia beniculturali arte anatolia artworkoftheday storiadellarte volgoarte beniculturali heritage artes museos artistlife masterpieces tesori italiani uffizigallery traveling arte loves monuments total monuments statue statues italia tuscanygram rome britishmuseum louvremuseum

text: An update for those of you with tickets for my talk on Friday evening part of the Totally Thames Foragers of the Foreshore Exhibition The bar is confirmed Also and more importantly both of my guests are primed and ready I will be delving even deeper into the mud to explore the notions of POSESSION and OBSESSION I ll be talking to Stuart Wyatt from the Museum of London about posession He s the man that identifies and records all objects of any significance from foreshore nobody knows more about the river s trove And I ll be discussing obsession with type designer Robert Green whose own obsession with Doves the lost Thames type took him inside the mind of its equally obsessed creator Even if you can t make the talk swing by and say hello on Friday afternoon I ll be there signing books between and You can look around at the mudlarked finds photographs paintings ceramics and crafts and there s even a short film that will transport you down onto the foreshore itself See you there LondonMudlark Mudlark Mudlarking

name: 2019-09-23 07.20.50 2138850330691409809_britishmuseum.jpg
text: An interesting and terrifying ghost on London Underground can be found at the abandoned British Museum station The station closed on the September Some people claim that the British Museum station on the Central Line is haunted by the ghost of an ancient Egyptian mummy from the nearby Museum The ghost is connected to the curse of the Amen Ra s tomb also know as the unlucky mummy Dressed in an impressive headdress the figure of an Egyptian Princess would return from the grave late at night and would wail and scream in the tunnels A more recent report states that these sounds can now be heard further down the track at Holborn station The rumours of the ghost grew so strong that a newspaper offered a reward to anyone who would spend the night there No one volunteered to do this In two years after the station s closure the story takes a stranger turn The comedy thriller Bulldog Jack used the legend as its premise which included a secret tunnel from the station to the Egyptian room at the Museum On the same night that the film was released two women disappeared from the platform at Holborn the next station along from where British Museum was Marks were later found on the walls of the closed station More sightings of the ghost were reported along with strange moanings from the walls of the tunnels Eventually the story was hushed up as London Underground has always denied the existence of the tunnel from the station to the Egyptian Room

text: PawsHistory Lesson When we think of an ancient dog we probably think of something almost more jackal like or wolf like and we definitely seen representations like that especially in Egyptian art but we also see for example mastiffs That s very much what you d expect a pet dog to look like right A lot of the dog votives that we know of came from what s now Iraq Some of them were made for royal patrons but others were commissioned by average lay people There s a healing goddess whose main attribute is a dog the Mesopotamian goddess Gula and we see her and her dog on a number of monumental stelae as well as smaller objects like cylinder seals and stamp seals So they occur in the visual record as both as pets and as these wild creatures There s that dual aspect to them On the one hand they are icons of the power of beastly nature so they re these fierce hunters But at the same time they re also definitely these extensions of us or things that work in tandem with humans jakestavis curatorial fellow at metmuseum and art history doctoral candidate at Columbia dog dad to animalhaven rescue Sandy

text: Repost by britishmuseum This Dante Gabriel Rossetti watercolour is on public display for the first time in decades catch it in our free prints and drawings exhibition in Room a It was painted by the artist in the s and sold to his friend William Morris as part of a series of seven medieval inspired watercolours The grisly scene shows two knights Dinadan and Breuze from the legend of King Arthur fighting while a dead man hangs from a tree behind and a woman is held against her will Find out more about this painting s story and discover other works recently donated from the collection of art historian curator and collector John Christian in our free display find out more via the link in our bio BritishMuseum Rosetti PreRaphaelite PreRaphaelites WilliamMorris VictorianHistory art painting watercolour exhibition London

text: Repost by britishmuseum This colourful cloisonn jar was made in th century China The enamel decoration shows a vigorous looking dragon chasing a pearl through clouds Brightly coloured enamelled objects like this were once thought to be vulgar and garish but by the early s they were considered suitable for the emperor s palace the reign mark suggests this jar was used in the Imperial Household In Room you can learn more about the fascinating history of China from BC to the present BritishMuseum China ChineseHistory cloisonn art design London Museum Ming

text: Didyouknow that the British Museum s reading room had the second largest dome in the world when it was built The round Reading Room was built in the museum s central courtyard in years after the museum first opened With a diameter of m the dome was the second largest in the world at the time second only to the Pantheon in Rome For perspective the dome of St Paul s Cathedral is m across The library was eventually moved in to the new British Library building near St Pancras The distinctive ceiling designed by Sir Norman Foster was added in and made the Great Court Europe s largest covered public square ottoberkeley British Museum blog on the Reading Room londonhistory museum facts historicalfacts london britishmuseum archaeology architecture londonarchitecture

text: People would shave their eyebrows because of cats It is thought cats were originally domesticated because they hunted mice that would eat stored grains but a recent study found that cats domesticated themselves They were never specifically sought out for domestication like dogs were but their coexistence with humans naturally developed from the mutually beneficial nature of the relationship with their hunting protecting the food stores While the exact history of human interaction with cats is still somewhat vague a shallow grave site discovered in in Cyprus dating to BCE during the Neolithic period contains the skeleton of a human buried ceremonially with stone tools In its own tiny grave centimeters from the human grave was an eight month old cat its body oriented in the same westward direction as the human skeleton Cats known in ancient Egypt as the mau played a large role in ancient Egyptian society They were associated with the goddesses Isis and Ba at Cats were sacred animals Killing a cat was absolutely forbidden and the Greek historian Herodotus reports that whenever a household cat died the entire family would mourn and shave their eyebrows They would then mummify them like humans and burry them in a sacred city Group of cat mummies Roman period linen britishmuseum Image rights britishmuseum cat cats catcontent kitty kitten catworld catlover catsofinstagram catsinsta catsofinsta animals kittens feline pet animal katze chat ancient greek roman egypt culture art arthistory history artblog britishmuseum london mummy

text: st Century AD Roman auxiliary cavalry helmet Dating from around AD and discovered in the s near Ely Cambridgeshire the wearer of this helmet was evidently involved in the Roman conquest of Britain which took place in the decades following the Claudian invasion of AD It s possible that the owner was an auxiliary trooper making up part of the campaign waged against the Iceni tribe of Eastern Britain by Governor Ostorius Scapula from AD Today only the helmet s decorative copper alloy casing remains which would have imparted very little protection by itself However it originally encased an iron core that has long since corroded away The cap neck guard and cheek guards were tinned which would have created the appearance of a gold band surrounding a silver helm This resplendent appearance would have been completed by a plumed crest affixed to the top of the helmet which has also been lost to decay BritishMuseum TheBritishMuseum BritishMuseumLondon Londinium AncientRome Artefacts RomanEmpire Archaeology ArchaeologyLovers Helmets RomanBritain RomanHelmet HistoricMonument History HistoryLover London HistoricLondon AncientHistory MuseumLover MuseumDay Museums HistoryNerd ClassicalHistory WitchamGravelHelmet Ely EastAnglia Iceni

text: A Young Girl in Profile c Painted by William Adolphe Bouguereau Born November La Rochelle France Died August La Rochelle France aged Oil on canvas x cm His work was characterized by a highly finished technically impeccable realism and a sentimental interpretation of his subject matter Bouguereau received many honours in the s and s and became for a time the most famous French painter of his day In his later years he decorated the chapels of several Parisian churches and painted religious compositions in a Pre Raphaelite style Throughout the course of his life Bouguereau executed known finished paintings although the whereabouts of many are still unknown Fig Details museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting realism williamadolphebouguereau larochelle france yourarttimes

text: Tutankhamun s Crook Flail The crook and flail were originally attributes of Osiris that became insignia of pharaonic authority The shepherd s crook stood for kingship and the flail stood for the fertility of the land By late Predynastic times the shepherd s crook was already an established symbol of rule The flail initially remained separate being depicted alone on some earliest representations of royal ceremonial Approximately by the time of the Second Dynasty the crook and flail became paired The only extant pharaonic examples of both the crook and flail come from the tomb of Tutankhamun The crook made of heavy bronze covered with alternating stripes of blue glass obsidian and gold while the flail s beads are made of gilded wood New Kingdom th Dynasty Valley of the Kings Luxor Egypt Photo tutankhamun london com tutankhamun tut kingtut pharaoh pharoah hieroglyphics museum britishmuseum london egypt valleyofthekings luxor cairo crook tomb facts instafacts facts hiero hieroglyphics heiroglyphics heiro archeology artefacts artifacts archaeology gold treasures ancient

text: Yunanistan da yer alan Epidaurus Antik Kenti tiyatrosu M y zy lda atlet heykeltra ve mimar olan Gen Polykleitos taraf ndan yap lm t r Son derece kaliteli akusti i ve simetrisi ile b y leyici bir tiyatrodur Antik Yunan d neminde oturma s ras varken Antik Roma d neminde s ra daha eklenerek kullan lm t r Epidaurus was a small polis in ancient Greece on the Argolid Peninsula at the Saronic Gulf The prosperity brought by the asclepeion enabled Epidaurus to construct civic monuments including the huge theatre that delighted Pausanias for its symmetry and beauty The ancient theatre of Epidaurus was designed by Polykleitos the Younger in the th century BC The original rows were extended in Roman times by another rows Bizi takip etmeyi unutmay n follow us ancient road ancient road ancient road archeotravel arkeoloji archaeology arqueologia archeologia italianart italia beniculturali arte sanat artworkoftheday storiadellarte volgoarte beniculturali heritage artes museos artistlife masterpieces tesori italiani uffizigallery traveling arte loves monuments total monuments statue statues italia tuscanygram rome britishmuseum louvremuseum

name: 2019-09-24 15.21.03 2139816811636532499_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Box Seats at the Theater the Gentleman and the Lady c Painted by Felix Vallotton Born December Lausanne Switzerland Died December Paris France Oil on canvas x cm He was a member the Nabis group who at the end of the th century combined the Post Impressionist techniques and style with new avant garde methods Although he never achieved the same level of prestige as Pierre Bonnard the leader of the Nabis Vallotton is a regular name in art auctions and his works are exhibited in the most reputable museums and galleries In his early years he became interested in portrait painting He occasionally returned to Switzerland where he painted landscapes in the region of Vaud In Paris he became interested in the art of engraving Two of his etchings were inspired by Jean Fran ois Millet and Rembrandt In he produced his first woodcuts and presented ten paintings in his debut at the Salon des Ind pendants Around this time he was initiated into the Nabis along with douard Vuillard Paul S rusier and Bonnard The Nabis which translates as the Prophets based their style subject matters and techniques on the works of Paul Gauguin Vincent Van Gogh Toulouse Lautrec and others The Nabis merged these separate styles into a single defined style that was later taken up by famous artists like C zanne and Matisse He exhibited with the Nabis in the Ambroise Vollard Gallery in Paris in and two years later in the Durand Ruel in the same city In he obtained French nationality The First World War had repercussions on their sales and caused financial problems Vallotton produced several works inspired by the conflict He went to live in Cagnes sur Mer in the winter of In November he was hospitalized and died after an operation for cancer A foundation for the study and promotion of the art of Vallotton was established in Lausanne in Between realism simplified stylisation and bitter criticism of the society of his time F lix Vallotton was above all a tireless worker creating more than canvases and engravings during his life

text: Today is Heritage Day in South Africa a day for honouring the cultural history and diversity of the country The holiday is known by two other names Shaka Day and Braai Day The first commemorates King Shaka Zulu c who was noted for uniting various clans into one Zulu kingdom and was the original focus of the September celebrations before The second celebrates the longstanding South African tradition of the braai or the grilling of meat over an open fire Our first watercolour is by an Unknown artist and depicts a Zulu warrior bearing the shield that Shaka is credited for introducing In our second painting by Dutch explorer Robert Jacob Gordon made a decade or so before Shaka s birth you can see members of the Gqunukhwebe clan enjoying braai Image Details https buff ly mh pEc Zulu Warrior th Century Unknown Artist Trustees of the British Museum CC BY NC SA https buff ly mh kjS The kraal of Captain Coba or Kob a chief of the Gqunukhwebe Robert Jacob Gordon Image courtesy Rijksmuseum Public Domain HeritageDay Braaiday SouthAfrica shakazulu zulu braai watercolour watercolourworld britishmuseum rijksmuseum

text: HEA E WA Anglo Saxon enthusiast and Theatre of War promoter Kieran wearing the Staffordshire Hoard Dave pommel shirt The design is based on a th century AD silver gilded pommel named by conservators as the Dave Pommel Believed to have been made in Scandinavia or Germany the pommel displays a bearded male head flanked either side by animals legs ending with paws The style is said to be inspired by continental Roman belt buckles originally displaying a male head proposed to be Neptune with dolphins shown either side of him This pommel comprised part of The Staffordshire Hoard the largest hoard of Anglo Saxon gold and silver metalwork yet found theatreofwarclothing britishhistory britishmuseum stokepotteriesmuseum staffordshirehoard staffordshirehoardhelmet anglosaxon archaeologist staffordshirehoard mercia anglosaxonperiod anglosaxonking birminghammuseumandartgallery potteriesmuseum

text: HEA E WA Now available theatreofwar bigcartel comIn Black Grey Red Green the Sutton Hoo Tiw T shirtThe design is based on an ornamentation found on a purse lid from the famous Anglo Saxon ship burial at Sutton Hoo dated to the early th century AD The image depicted is proposed to be Tiw or Tyr Old Norse Tiw was another deity of chief importance to the Anglo Saxons as he was the god of war swordplay and the sky The purse lid from Sutton Hoo is the richest of its kind yet found The lid was made to cover a leather pouch containing gold coins It hung by three hinged straps from the waist belt and was fastened by a gold buckle The lid had totally decayed but was probably made of whalebone a precious material in early Anglo Saxon England anglosaxonperiod england englisheritage anglosaxon anglosaxonengland suttonhoonationaltrust suffolk suttonhoo anglian anglosaxonking theatreofwarclothing northerneuropean britishhistory britishmuseum suttonhoo suttonhoohelmet englishhistory theatreofwarclothing

text: INTERESTING FACTS ABOUT THE BRITISH MUSEUM The Museum had its own tube station for over years The station opened in but was closed in September when the new Holborn station opened The Museum gate was once guarded by a cat named Mike He guarded the main gate between and When he died his obituary appeared in the Evening Standard and TIME magazine The Museum s collection was evacuated during the Second World War Banksy had an unofficial exhibit at the MuseumIn May world famous street artist Banksy snuck a rock depicting a caveman with a shopping trolley into the British Museum It stayed there for two days before anyone noticed it Mozart visited the Museum in the s Which fact surprised you the most

text: In my hunt for authentic Xi an food in London I tracked down Chef Wei at her latest venture Bloomsbury restaurant Master Wei The restaurant opened on March th Because that s my birthday says Wei with a smile The area around the British Museum is filling up with Chinese restaurants Master Wei is a five minute walk from the current home of the Elgin Marbles located in a quiet side street with a pleasant outdoor seating area The interior of the restaurant is bright and spacious A bar with a map of Shaanxi province as a backdrop lines the rear wall The guests are mostly Chinese with a few Westerners Tilly Wei s assistant says this is a great compliment If the Chinese come it means the flavour is authentic she confides Wei makes everything and I mean EVERYTHING from scratch She creates a spice water by boiling dried spices until they release their aromas Her sauces are layered in flavour she is careful with chilli and Sichuan peppercorn lest they mask the more delicate notes in her dishes Making the dough both for noodles and bread is a drawn out process with bursts of labour and long intervals where the dough must rest Her dishes look so simple but the effort that she puts into each component is huge Highly recommended Who can name all the spices in the photo masterwei xianfood foodwriter foodblogger xiancuisine chineserestaurant londonchinese noodles biangbiangnoodles instafood foodie foodporn foodgram chefsofinstagram cheflife foodies carbs delicious northernchinesefood chinesefood london bloomsbury londonrestaurants chef britishmuseum londonfood vegetarian plantbased

text: Laurence Stephen Lowry RBA RA The undisputed King of the North West Lowry is famous for painting scenes of life in the industrial districts of North West England in the mid th century He developed a distinctive style of painting and is best known for his urban landscapes peopled with human figures often referred to as matchstick men He painted mysterious unpopulated landscapes brooding portraits and the unpublished marionette works Due to his use of stylized figures and the lack of weather effects in many of his landscapes he is sometimes characterized as a na ve My favourite period of Lowry was from where he really captured the bleak English condition of the age I also love his lonely sparse still seascapes but unfortunately got hounded for taking photos so didn t get any photos of them These are some of my favourite Lowry s seen in The Lowry Collection in Salford the Manchester Art Gallery A truly unique artist england englishart britishhistory britishmuseum britishart britain lowry lslowry naive naiveart stickfigures modernist modernart modernism salford manchester manchesterart manchesterartgallery salfordart salfordartgallery industrial industrialart interior interiordesign london europeanart europe

name: 2019-09-25 15.07.17 2140534655416467543_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Sometimes it s the tiniest of objects that tell the greatest stories This piece of roof tile has been in a serious fire It s blackened twisted and almost vitrified on one side I picked it up from the foreshore in central London almost exactly where Samuel Pepys sat off shore in a boat years ago watching London burn For four long days the Great Fire raged through the City and the docks along the riverside It destroyed houses and churches and burned the wings of the pigeons that roosted in their eaves so that they fell down into the inferno below Liquid lead from the roof of Old St Paul s ran through the streets and the fire was so hot it melted steel that was stored in the docks When the fire was over London was in ashes A city that was made of wood was rebuilt in brick and stone The charred rubble it left behind was used to fill holes and taken east by the cartload to stabilise the marshes at Wapping In the turmoil some might have been dumped in the river which is how this burned fragment of roof tile with its round hole for the wooden peg that once held it on the roof of a medieval building ended up on the foreshore Londonmudlark Mudlark Mudlarking Mudlarkingbook

name: 2019-09-25 15.20.30 2140541306636402885_britishmuseum.jpg
text: HEA E WA Theatre of War promoter Grace boginka wearing a shirt displaying a design based on on the early th century AD Dancing Warrior pressblech from the helmet found in Mound at Sutton Hoo Suffolk England The Dancing Warriors or Spear Dancers image is shown on many artefacts found across Northern Europe and is believed to be emblematic of a religious ceremony invoking Odin Woden Wotan This is symbolised by the dancer s headwear being comprised of two birds believed to be Odin s ravens Huginn Munnin terminating in the centre The earliest known images made by Germanic people s alluding to the weapon dancer s is the sword dancers from Flimlingoje in East Sealand Denmark The motifs are embossed on gilt silver foils on a pair of rd century AD cups showing naked dancers leaping with drawn swords and animals bound about in scenes full of life and ecstasy Many further examples are shown on scenes from the th century AD Gallehus Horns the th century AD bronze cast plates from Bj rnhovda in Torslunda on land the fragmentary th century AD silver foil from Caenby Lincolnshire and on the th century AD silver foil from Obrigheim Germany theatreofwarclothing ironage ironagehistory suttonhoo nationalmuseet britishmuseum britishhistory britishart britisharchaeology germanic wolfwarrior northerneuropean germanicironage sweden nature sweden nationalmuseet nationalmuseetcopenhagen nationalmuseumstockholm swedishhistory icelandicsagas vikingtattoo northeurope

text: This dazzling gold object was made for a member of the imperial family in China in the early s It was part of a pair that were used to decorate the ends of a pillow The design features two dragons and the object is inlaid with semi precious stones imported to China from Southeast Asia India and Sri Lanka all important places for Chinese trade during the Ming dynasty See this object on display and discover more about Chinese history in Room BritishMuseum China ChineseHistory gold gemstones art design London Museum Ming

text: Kerrrrrrang Manga is a contradiction It s a global phenomenon but is still deeply rooted in Japanese culture It s big business too but with enough genres to cater for tastes from the everyday to the perverse But trying to make sense of all of manga s contradictions can result in more hrrrrrumph than kerrrrrang It s best to find your own corner of the manga world to enjoy If you re interested in reading more my article More hrrrrrumph than kerrrrrang The Citi Exhibition Manga can be found by clicking the link in the bio August Colossal Titan from Attack of the Titans originally featured in Naruto by Kishimoto Masahi b from The Citi Exhibition Manga at the British Museum London from rd May to th August personal photo manga anime hokusai katushikahokusai kyosai kawanabekyosai hagio motohagio tagame gengorotagame britishmuseum japan japaneseart talkingaboutart art

text: This piece was created based on a sketch form the British Museum I was drawing the Sekhmet statues spent a lot of time looking with my thoughts wandering aimlessly The Egyptian section of the museum is always so busy but I find the cool stone statues extremely atmospheric and I was always drawn to these strong anthrophomorphic female statues I started resarching wwax anatomical models at the time and reading about the anatomical Venuses of the European th century anatomical collections My brain couldn t resist the idea of combining the two especially with the ancient Egyptianss relationship to anatomy Swipe right for detail draing polychromos colouringpencils graphite britishmuseum sekhmet goddess egyptian egyptiansculpture dissection anatomicalvenus anatomicalmodel

text: Liverpool I m having a ripper time up North Manchester was great but Liverpool knocked my socks off Unbelievable town so rich with history and the architecture on par with Paris or Rome The Walker Art Gallery has the best collection of Victorian and Pre Raphaelite art I ve ever seen Even many artists which are prevalent in the Belle Epoque Collection like Albert Moore Henry Fuseli George Romney David Hockney Frederick Leighton Gustave Dore John William Waterhouse Plus the Glasgow Boys Sickert And everything is The Beatles I m still giddy from my day visit I will visit again soon what a city england englishart britishhistory britishmuseum britishart britain lowry lslowry naive naiveart stickfigures modernist modernart modernism thebeatles manchester manchesterart manchesterartgallery livepool walkerartgallery industrial industrialart interior interiordesign london europeanart europe

text: Feel privileged to have my portrait and a selection of finds featured in the Foragers of the Foreshore exhibition the most expansive display of artefacts recovered from the Thames ever staged It s taking place at the Bargehouse Oxo Wharf until this Sunday Each mudlark featured has been interviewed about the attractions of searching the foreshore and their favourite finds Myself and edjbucknall can be heard chatting th Century boozing roman hair pins medieval harp music Soviet WW ammo prehistoric beads and suitable footwear among other topics at the link below https totallythames org foragers ed bucknall malcolm russell Shouts out to awesome photographer han smiles who braved a cold February foreshore to accompany me on a nightlark conceiver and curator of the exhibition flo finds totallythames who have made Foragers a key part of this year s Thames Festival and the entire mudlarking community mudlarkingfinds mudlarking mudlark beachcombing seaglass totallythames london riverthames southbank oxotower treasurehunting vintage archaeology britishmuseum museumoflondon metaldetecting metaldetctingfinds antique beachcombing foundobjects foundobject art tatemodern tudor history historylesson arthistory

text: This is the smallest stoneware ink pot I ve ever found Usually they are the size of the larger one in the second picture and look very much like pork pies Before the th century ink production was pretty much a cottage industry but with the increasing number of people able to write more ink was needed and production was commercialised Stoneware ink pots like this corked and sealed with wax were sold for just a penny Stoneware ink bottles had the benefit of keeping the ink away from the light Londonmudlark mudlark mudlarking

text: The Cosplay Journal Vol PRE ORDER NOW It s finally time volume of The Cosplay Journal is coming And it s bigger than ever Featuring an exclusive interview with Nicole Rousmaniere the curator of The British Museum s Citi Manga Exhibition and a photoshoot in The British Museum itself On top of this this volume looks at how cosplay can positively help your mental health and wellbeing with an interview with Wish Godmother who uses cosplay to combat her PTSD as well as talking with disabled cosplay activist Ekko Cosplay about how disability is viewed in the geek community Woodsmoke and Words tells us about gender and cosplay and what it s like being a non binary cosplayer with help from an amazing group of trans non binary costume makers There are all the regular features and much more in volume The Cosplay Journal is a coffee table periodical focusing on the Diversity and Craft of cosplay We want to show that not only can anyone from any walk of life be involved in cosplay but also that we are all capable of learning new skills creating amazing things and bringing joy into our own and other people s lives through the art form of costume making The Cosplay Journal s mission is to dispel the myths about cosplay and cosplayers as well as promoting cosplay as way into a new world and maybe even a new career The Cosplay Journal Vol features pages of stunning photography interviews and articles and is available to pre order now from the links on the News page on our website link in bio now https markosia com the cosplay journal vol pre order now markosia cosplay costume captainmarvel ukcosplay discworld manga britishmuseum

text: Celebrating years of Iniva The exhibition Time Machine Ancient Egypt and Contemporary Art contested the idea that ancient Egyptian artefacts held by the British Museum were stagnant remnants of the past disconnected from the present Installed in the vast Egyptian Sculpture gallery the works by twelve artists achieved a rare juxtaposition of ancient and contemporary art Featured artists included Liliane Karnouk Rita Keegan Marc Quinn Peter Randall Page Alexander Mihaylovich David Hiscock Igor Mitroraj Jiri Kolar Kate Whiteford Martin Riches Stephen Cox Andy Goldsworthy and James Putnam Image credit Liliane Karanouk detail of installation showing railings test tubes with palms and side of the sarcophagus decorated with frieze of gods Iniva timemachine contemporaryart exhibition britishmuseum LilianeKarnouk RitaKeegan MarcQuinn PeterRandallPage AlexanderMihaylovich DavidHiscock IgorMitroraj JiriKolar KateWhiteford MartinRiches StephenCox AndyGoldsworthy JamesPutnam

text: Seianti Hanunia Tlesnasa Seianti Chiusi Painted sarcophagus of Seianti Hanunia Tlesnasa BCE The brightly painted sarcophagus of the Etruscan aristocratic woman Seianti was discovered in near Tuscany and was subsequently sold along with its contents a skeleton and some grave belongings to the British Museum The deceased woman s name is inscribed in Etruscan along the base of the chest She must have belonged to one of the richest families of Chiusi She has been depicted as a mature lady who gestures to adjust her veil She leans against a pillow and holds a mirror in her other hand gazing into the distance archaeologicalmuseum archaeologia archaeology archaeologylife historylovers archaeologylove museum museum lovers etruscanart history britishmuseum etruscan antiquity sculptures art arthistory culture storiantica throwback london historia museumsaroundtheworld archaeologist ancientcivilization artefacts historicalplace igworldclub archaeology sarcophagus

text: K the Kollwitz Self Portrait and Call of Death It is a fortunate coincidence that the britishmuseum is showing a selection of K the Kollwitz prints at the same time as the exhibition on Helene Schjerfbeck royalacademyarts These two great women artists were not only contemporaries but they both produced a number of scrutinising and strong Self Portraits throughout their lives It is interesting to compare their self portraits which share an uncompromising way of confronting age and mortality reflecting the intensity and darkness of the troubled times they both lived through k thekollwitz britishmuseum exhibition portraitofanartist selfportrait selbstbildnis prints druckgraphik departmentofdrawingsandprints lithograph callofdeath RufdesTodes heleneschjerfbeck royalacademy comparison womenartists germanartist finnishartist womanartist femaleartist k nstlerin troubledtimes

text: Elegant Lady with a Bouquet of Roses Painted by Emile Vernon Born March Blois France Died January Blois France aged First studied design at the School of Fine Arts in Tours where he won the first prize for design in at the age of sixteen He moved to Paris when he was eighteen to study with the famed teachers and artists William Bouguereau and Auguste Trupheme at the Ecole Des Beaux Arts In he had two exhibitions first he participated at The Exposition of Fine Arts and Decorative Arts in Paris and later the same year exhibited at the Salon des Artistes Francais and from then on Emile Vernon exhibited regularly at the Paris Salon from to Vernon specialised in painting portraits and genre scenes The fact that he mastered the graphics of his work and painted the lighting in a clever seductive manner made his portraits charming and of a very high quality and are much in demand in the America Canada and Japan Emile Vernon also received numerous commissions for decorative murals as well as oil painting for the theater of Chatellerault in He also created paintings for the Nevers Theater In he exhibited at The Royal Academy in London the floral painting Roses Emile Vernon died in at the age of Fig Details museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting bouquet roses emilevernon blois france yourarttimes

name: 2019-09-27 06.00.12 2141708853933711508_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Thirty years ago to the day aged twenty six I took a RoyalJordanian flight from KuwaitCity to London in order to pursue my postgraduate studies in Aquatic Resource Management at King s College London I was unable to continue my studies largely due to an overwhelming sense of ancestral loss and the questioning of whether or not I was meant to be a biologist I left college after passing my exams A s B and my professor encouraged me to hand in my thesis the following year Then SaddamHussein decided to invade the land of my formative years and the whole world collapsed on my already crushed head Overnight I became homeless penniless and nation less The darkest hour of my life to date Working as a musician at the much lamented MuseumOfMankind of the BritishMuseum for the PalestinianCostumeExhibition saved my life literally so It helped turn me into a musicologist and so the ology travelled from Bio to Music Being an independent musician remains the greatest struggle More than any other Contrary to what many may believe being based in the UK as a practitioner of the neocolonialist tag that s so called WorldMusic has hindered my career rather than help it It s time for shedding and for a possibly different career Life has not been easy since I returned to the land of my birth and yet I am grateful for each and every day I am grateful to my husband my in laws my neighbours and my friends for giving me a permanent makeshift home that is floating somewhere between Palestine and Kuwait As for the latter I feel it s time to open the golden box in which I hid it all these years I simply wanted to protect myself from all the pain of what had happened to my family and childhood friends as a result of a reckless and evil invasion that has left the MiddleEast in the gory state of chaos we re all witnessing today Thank you dear God for everything September September HomePhoto BoushahriPhotoStudio Salmiya Kuwait

name: 2019-09-27 14.39.51 2141970397493589749_britishmuseum.jpg
text: A Girl in the Garden c Painted by Olga Wisinger Florian Born November Vienna Austria Died February Grafenegg Austria aged Oil on canvas x cm Olga Wisinger Florian the most important representative of the Austrian Mood Impressionism Stimmungsimpressionismus was born in a middle class family in Vienna She first studied piano and became a solo concert pianist Her piano instructor was Julius Epstein who was also Gustav Mahler s music teacher at the Vienna Conservatory In her music career ended due to a hand injury She got married shortly after to a pharmacist Franz Wisinger and had a son Oskar in During the mid s Wisinger Florian turned to painting She studied painting with Melchor Fritsch and August Schaeffer and from was the first private student of painter Emil Jakob Schindler Along with Schindler and his disciples Carl Moll Marie Egner and Tina Blau Lang Olga Wisinger Florian made many study trips They famously painted together in the Plankenberg area As of her paintings were regularly seen at annual exhibitions at the K nstlerhaus as well as the Secession As a young painter Wisinger Florian was completely under her mentor Schindler s influence Her painting of light and mood as well as her choice of motifs alleys gardens fields show strong similarities to Schinder s works After breaking with Schindler in Wisinger Florian developed an increasingly more independent style She then used intense colors and moved from realistic landscape expressionism to dynamic landscape and flower images that were ahead of her time Olga Wisinger Florian was one of the most important painters of the century Her social contacts provided her with an elite circle of buyers Vistors to her studio included Archduchess Clothilde Bavaria s Prince Regent Luitpold and the King of Bulgaria Emperor Franz Joseph I purchased one of her paintings In with her vision diminishing Olga Wisinger Florian withdrew from her active social life She died in Grafenegg Lower Austria She received an honorary grave in Vienna s Central Cemetery

text: When we think of the British Museum we see a grand neo classical building built from Portland stone However before the building that we know today was built there was an earlier museum housed in MontaguHouse a late th century mansion in GreatRussellStreet in the Bloomsbury Montagu House was built for Ralph Montagu st Duke of Montagu and was the grandest aristocratic residence erected in London although actually in the county of Middlesex at the time It would remain the London home of the Montagu family until being sold to the Trustees of the BritishMuseum in becoming then the home of the museum until demolition in the s to make way for larger premises Founded in the British Museum was essentially the collections of the Irish physician and scientist SirHansSloane However in acquiring Montagu House the museum s trustees had bought a property and site befitting what was destined to become a national indeed international collection Our antique print from the collection of Frontispiece Ltd was published on this day September th in and recorded the demolition of Montagu House In a supporting article the Illustrated London News states As Montague House the old British Museum is disappearing by piecemeal and the ornate French plan is giving way to to the comparatively severe portico and colonnade of Sir Sir Robert Smirke s new Museum we have deemed the present state of the two buildings a fit subject for illustration I have known this antique print for very many years but it was not until this morning that on reading the accompanying text did I realise that both the old and new museum appear in the illustration for peering through the centre of the engraving is the facade of the newly erected structure

text: Happy Friday to everyone Some fact about us when we visit a museum Antonio really likes to stop and read everything he sometimes takes the audioguides for more information He is really patient he is calm and he doesn t rush anything I Marina am like a child in a museum depending of what I see I will stop to read or just to look at it or not I m really impatient and I m always looking for something to catch my attention Sometimes this is a good thing like this view from a small window of the inside of the British Museum For the rest I envy Antonio a lot Feliz viernes a todos Algunos hechos sobre nosotros cuando visitamos museos A Antonio le gusta pararse y leer todo a veces coge las audiogu as para tener a n m s informaci n Es tranquilo paciente y no le gusta tener prisa por nada Yo Marina soy como un ni o en un museo dependiendo de lo que vea me paro y lo miro o no Soy siempre impaciente y espero a que algo llame mi atenci n A veces esto es bueno como esta vista desde una peque a ventana del interior del Museo Brit nico Por el resto envidio much simo a Antonio

text: Young Woman Wearing a Hat Painted by Pierre Auguste Renoir Born February Limoges France Died December Cagnes sur Mer France aged His father was a tailor and Renoir was given an apprenticeship at a porcelain painter He then had the opportunity to study at the Ecole des Beaux Arts He was a fellow student of Monet Sisley and Bazille he went on summer painting trips with them to Chailly and Fountainbleau He studied the eighteenth century paintings in the Louvre and also met Corot Millet and Diaz His art was noted for its vibrant combination of colours In classic impressionist style he avoided rigid lines and merged objects giving a sense of dream like consciousness He also painted many portraits of women often in nude In he visited Algeria and then Italy In Italy he was deeply impressed by the Italian Masters After meeting Cezanne near Marseilles Renoir sought to break away from Impressionism by developing a new structural style of his own Yet he never abandoned his techniques of colour that he learnt during his impressionist period and he developed a combination of classical styles of applying paint with an impressionist perspective of colour In he married Aline Victorine Charigot a dressmaker twenty years his junior Renoir included her in many of his future paintings depicting family life They had three children including Jean Renoir a noted filmmaker Towards the end of the nineteenth century he gained increasing fame and respect In the French state bought one of his paintings At the Piano During the last years of his life Renoir was crippled by arthritis unable to move his hands freely he continued to paint some great masterpieces using a brush strapped to his arm museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery text: Have you spotted the Albrecht D rer exhibition that s just opened at the Albertina in Vienna Learn more here https buff ly mUwGQN D rer was an exceptional painter who created detailed studies of animals and plants This picture of a rock face details the texture colour and irregularities in each layer of rock as well as the plants and mosses that have found a footing on it Here s a painting he made of the muzzle of an ox which picks out the cracked skin on its dark nose and every stray hair https buff ly lPhsfP Some of D rer s landscapes look surprisingly modern like this study of a lake and trees where the cloudy but sun splashed sky is only hastily described with colourful washes of paint https buff ly ns AEQ Image Details https buff ly mRG MX Untitled Study of a rock face c Albrecht D rer Trustees of the British Museum CC BY NC SA albrechtdurer albertina vienna watercolour thewatercolourworld britishmuseum

text: One of my favourite works in the British Museum Tucked away on an obscure shelf I was lost for words when I first saw it It had a modest scale and devotional skill in the carving It s nice to see works so slow in their making with that almost filmic quality of revealed narrative In this it seems an early Proustian search for lost time a quality that I love to put into my own paintings detailedart britishmuseum

text: Repost mythology in art Astarte is the Hellenized form of the Middle Eastern goddess Astoreth Northwest Semitic a form of Ishtar East Semitic worshipped from the Bronze Age through classical antiquity The name is particularly associated with her worship in the ancient Levant among the Canaanites and Phoenicians She was also celebrated in Egypt following the importation of Levantine cults there The name Astarte is sometimes also applied to her cults in Mesopotamian cultures like Assyria and Babylonia Astarte was connected with fertility sexuality and war Her symbols were the lion the horse the sphinx the dove and a star within a circle indicating the planet Venus She has been known as the deified morning and or evening star Queen of the Night relief old Babylonian period BC From Southern Mesopotamia may represent the goddesses Ishtar Lilith or Ereshkigal The BritishMuseum London britishmuseum astarte ishtar JohnSingerSargent mythology mythologyart

text: Watched Hokusai by British Museum tonight and was a bit disappointed the movie is actually a promo video for the Hokusai exhibition in It emphasised on how great Hokusai was in the eyes of the westerners but told little about how the Japanese culture social and political situation in Japan affected Hokusai i was impressed by scholar ROGER KEYES who spent his own life on studying ukiyoe and Hokusai He cried a bit when he was making compliments to Hokusai and i could feel the same as i cried every time when watching Hokusai s documentary he was really a hero in the art history and role model for those who love arts and crafts hokusai britishmuseum greatwave k musea ua

text: Nautilus pompilius This standing cup is made from a nautilus shell mounted in silver gilt and chased The shell is engraved with dragons among clouds The engraved band around lip are supported at sides by marine terminal figures In front by band of strapwork with grotesque mask The back of the mounted shell represent a sea monster with open mouth On its back there is the infant Hercules with a serpent in one hand the other hand holds a modern spear The baluster stem with festoons of fruit The base in form of bird s claw britishmuseum Standing cup Made in Padua Italy or in Germany for the mounts circa and Guangzhou China for the nautilus shell carving in the late th century or the early th century Gilded silver and nautilus shell British Museum London britishmuseum Coupe mont e R alis Padoue Italie ou en Allemagne pour les montures vers et Guangzhou Chine pour le la coquille de Nautile sculpt e la fin du XV me ou au d but du XVI me si cle Argent dor et coquille de Nautile British Museum Londres britishmuseum th post of DailyMuseum This week Unusual materials

text: Repost britishmuseum trijota This Dante Gabriel Rossetti watercolour is on public display for the first time in decades catch it in our free prints and drawings exhibition in Room a It was painted by the artist in the s and sold to his friend William Morris as part of a series of seven medieval inspired watercolours The grisly scene shows two knights Dinadan and Breuze from the legend of King Arthur fighting while a dead man hangs from a tree behind and a woman is held against her will Find out more about this painting s story and discover other works recently donated from the collection of art historian curator and collector John Christian in our free display find out more via the link in our bio BritishMuseum Rosetti PreRaphaelite PreRaphaelites WilliamMorris VictorianHistory art painting watercolour exhibition London

name: 2019-09-30 05.18.26 2143862158505523553_britishmuseum.jpg
text: UK Travel Today has been mostly overcast and showery This morning I set off to Camden in the northwest of London Camden is known for its trendy street shopping the Camden markets and canals It s Sunday here so I was expecting it to be busy but not as crowd crushingly so as it was It was still a good morning though despite the crowds and rain I could have made lots of purchases in the interesting craft and antiques stalls but resisted On the high street shopping precinct there seemed to be competition between the shop owners see who could out do each another with their elaborate decorative facades above the shopfronts The many food stalls and eating places looked interesting and smelled great but lunch was elsewhere so I caught the Tube back to Euston station and my lunch appointment for gluten free cod and chips at a recommended pub the Lord John Russell near my accommodation They lived up to the recommendation so I ll probably return before I leave After lunch I strolled down Oxford Street I was good today so no shopping apart from a more sturdy travel umbrella and ended up at Marble Arch where I reacquainted myself with the Still Water horse head sculpture It was raining fairly heavy by now so I decided to catch the Tube back towards my accommodation and spend the rest of the afternoon at the British Museum which is just around the corner Tomorrow I m off to Canterbury and Margate u london camden camdenmarket britishmuseum lordjohnrussellpub

text: Julia Margaret Cameron c Painted by George Frederic Watts Born February Marylebone Middlesex England Died July Compton Surrey England Oil on canvas cm Watts was frequently ill during childhood and spent a great deal of time in bed drawing stories for himself His first major success as painter took place in the spring of Watts entered the competition for the decoration of the Houses of Parliament and won the prize of for his drawing of Caractacus led Captive through the Streets of Rome He brilliant depiction of historical personalities impressed the judges and set the stage for a lucrative art career His fellow competitors included historical painter Benjamin Haydon Haydon whom was beset by financial difficulties became so upset over the younger artists win that he took his own life Watts used his winnings to travel to Italy According to Art historian William Loftus Hare Italy and particularly Florence was perpetual fascination and inspiration to Watts There he imbibed the influences of Orcagna and Titian In Watts fell in love with a beautiful young actress young enough to be his daughter The artist courted Miss Ellen Terry with old fashioned gallantry and road to her home on a white horse begging her to marry him Terry was impressed with the art and elegance of his lifestyle and wished to please her parents by making an advantageous marriage They married on February shortly before her th birthday when Watts was Terry and Watts were separated after only ten months of marriage during which she took a break from the stage returning by The great artist was variable and uncertain Though humble and self deprecatory to an extreme degree he made mistakes from which he could escape only with great difficulty and he suffered much from depression and melancholy The aging painter continued to earn great renown for his luminous portraits and monumental allegorical paintings Towards the end of his life Watts gave most of his work to British museums Fig Details

name: 2019-09-30 14.48.17 2144148974634080755_britishmuseum.jpg
text: EARLY MORNING EXPLORERS AT THE BRITISH MUSEUM I had a dream that we were the only people in the British Museum Madness right Well this dream came true yesterday when we attended the first EarlyMorningExplorers BritishMuseum I ll stop being flippant The fact is that noisy bright and busy environments are completely unmanageable for families with children on the autism spectrum And the lack of understanding from others makes the inevitable meltdowns even harder to cope with So the treasures which are our national museum packed to the rafters with tourists and day trippers are out of bounds for many families The good news is that many museums now run special events aimed at families with children on the autism spectrum and others who would benefit from a quieter environment There s less people lights are dimmed or dark areas lit hand driers are turned off and special sensory areas are set up Staff are trained and even better there won t be a single raised eyebrow as every parent will have first hand experience of autistic behaviours For their first Early Morning Explorers the British Museum opened up their Greek galleries and put on brilliant interactive storytelling with warnings about any noises make your own Trojan horse crafts object handling and sensory play trays It was brilliant to be able enjoy this museum with the kids one we normally avoid More pics in story highlights AUTISM IN MUSEUM EVENTS The next Early Morning Explorers at the BM will be on Sunday February FREE booking required Follow autisminmuseums run by tinctureofmuseum for more museum autism events If you know anyone who might benefit from this post please send it to them I had the most heartwarming response to one of my stories from a parent who dreams of taking their child with autism to a big museum but hadn t before realised that these events run Hopefully by sharing events like this this parent and others like them can have their dreams come true for a few hours at least If you could have one museum all to yourself which would it be autismfriendly britishmuseum kidsinmuseums

name: 2019-09-30 20.11.25 2144311611102640563_britishmuseum.jpg
text: LANDMARKS Throughout our lives we all have landmarks and yesterday I went back to one for me I spent several happy years in this beautiful mansion house on Great Russell Street and every morning I woke up to the view of the British Museum and the odd mouse scurrying across the carpet of my bedroom The souvenir of Victorian architecture is mice finding warmth and shelter from the London rain I found going back quite emotional It s my old stomping ground when I first started working in London and I have many happy memories of hosting roast dinners friends staying over meeting an international set of flat mates some of whom I adore that s you Grace and Eleanora by the way and the Rosetta Stone being housed across the road from me You know that Frank Sinatra line regrets I ve had a few Well that was how I was feeling yesterday When I lived in Bloomsbury I was so big and I struggled to walk to the end of the street Taxis were used to go everywhere I must have funded the corner shop and the fish and chip shop was as far as I could waddle Yesterday reminiscing it felt like back then I was trapped when essentially I was anything but that I had all the means to go anywhere and don t get me wrong I was living a good life but it wasn t healthy I had London on my doorstep and yesterday I was wishing I had turned things around sooner I then had a word with myself and told myself NO What is the point in having regrets I cannot change the past but I do have the power to change the now and my future I get asked from people who want to loose weight is how do I get started How do I stick to it How do I not give up My answer is do it when it s right for you Don t be forced into it You don t have to do it You need to want to do it for YOU When your mind is in the right space it will happen This is what happened for me and once I started it was like going downhill you build on each step and before you know it it will be part of your routine For your little piece of Monday motivation take advice from old blue eyes I may have a few regrets but I DID IT MY WAY If I can do it so can you

text: SELFIES EN EL MUSEO DE SAN JUAN DE LA MATASantalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO Una vez inaugurados podr n programarse exposiciones temporales o permanentes Los tres primeros museos ya se han inaugurado en Lapuebla de Labarca en San Juan de la Mata y en Madrid y continuar n en Ponferrada Alovera Arganza Sancti Petri Vitoria Trillo SELFIES IN THE MUSEUM OF SAN JUAN DE LA MATASantalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose goal is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM Once opened temporary or permanent exhibitions may be scheduled The first three museums have already opened in Lapuebla de Labarca in San Juan de la Mata and in Madrid and will continue in Ponferrada Alovera Arganza Sancti Petri Vitoria Trillo selfies reinasofiamuseum museodelprado caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma museedorsay louvre met britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi yaleartgallery galleriaborghese gettymuseum sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

text: Tableware and Fruits c Painted by Henri Matisse Born December Le Cateau Cambr sis France Died November Nice France aged Oil on canvas cm Location The State Hermitage Museum Saint Petersburg Henri Matisse is widely regarded as the greatest colorist of the th century and as a rival to Pablo Picasso in the importance of his innovations He emerged as a Post Impressionist and first achieved prominence as the leader of the French movement Fauvism Although interested in Cubism he rejected it and instead sought to use color as the foundation for expressive decorative and often monumental paintings As he once controversially wrote he sought to create an art that would be a soothing calming influence on the mind rather like a good armchair Still life and the nude remained favorite subjects throughout his career North Africa was also an important inspiration and towards the end of his life he made an important contribution to collage with a series of works using cut out shapes of color He is also highly regarded as a sculptor According to David Rockefeller Matisse s final work was the design for a stained glass window installed at the Union Church of Pocantico Hills near the Rockefeller estate north of New York City It was his final artistic creation the maquette was on the wall of his bedroom when he died in November of Rockefeller writes Installation was completed in Matisse died of a heart attack at the age of on November He is interred in the cemetery of the Monast re Notre Dame de Cimiez near Nice museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting tableware fruits henrimatisse lecateaucambresis nice france rockefellercenter yourarttimes

text: Stolen from Africa LITERALLY These are a collection Benin Bronzes that British soldiers looted from the Kingdom of Benin during the colonial era The Kingdon of Benin Nigerian Government have been fighting the British Government for decadea to have them returned back Such intricate beautifully crafted pieces demonstrating the sophistication of African art sculptures Sad to learn the history of their theft and the ongoing battle to have them returned Although amazing to see touch and feel in person it would be a better feeling to travel to Benin to see them in their rightful home Some Bronzes have been returned however a majority of the collection is in the possession of European museums and private art collectors Sadly there are many more stolen African pieces on display in the British musem All I could do was shake my head the whole time britishmuseum london theafrofusionspot ootd art benin beninbronzes nigeria africanart africanstyle backgirlmagic museum colonialism british blackgirlswhoblog melanin ghanagirl stylish africanfashionbloggers stolenfromafrica love toronto africanbloggers torontobloggers instalike instafashion instastyle picoftheday photooftheday

text: The Great Court at the British Museum Europe s largest covered square is a perfect spot to grab a coffee before the museum officially opens This may be our favorite museum in the world we have been here so many times and yet are always surprised and delighted by learning something new seeing something beautiful or just contemplating the breadth of human history For me no trip to London is complete without a stop here even on business and with only an hour to spare it was always worth the stop But if you never visit in person you can still have have an excellent virtual tour I would recommend A History of the World in Objects the co production with BBC Radio or the book which can help put one s arms around the incredible collection in a discrete and less overwhelming way britishmuseum greatcourt london

name: 2019-10-01 21.44.11 2145083075906517924_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Colnaghi is pleased to present at Frieze Masters this magnificent Late Archaic bronze statuette of a Centaur from ca BC h cm The statuette was probably part of a large cauldron or a tripod stand and seems to be the largest known example from the Archaic Greek period Unlike later representations it depicts the hybrid creature fully human in front encumbered with half a horse in the rear Centaurs were popular in Archaic and Classical Greek art The most frequently depicted episode was when they were invited to attend the wedding of their half brother Pirithous but became drunk and attempted to carry off the bride and other female guests In the ensuing battle most of the Centaurs were killed Homer Odyssey ff Centaurs therefore symbolized mankind s unbridled appetite for food and wine and violent sexuality centaur battleofthecentaurs battleoflapithsandcentaurs greekmythology classicalmythology parthenonsculptures homerodyssey ancientart greekantiquities greekart greekhistory ancientgreece archaicgreece regentspark artoftheancientworld londonartevents timeoutlondon timeout benbrownfinearts britishmuseum colnaghi britishmuseum timeoutart artnews benbrownfinearts friezeartfair frieze magazine jorge coll colnaghifoundation

text: The King s Library at the British Museum built and designed by Sir Robert Smirke to house George III s library which was given to the nation by George IV and moved to the new British Library in This magnificent room now houses an exhibition on the th century Enlightenment and with its classical statues and numerous cabinets of curiosities feels like walking round a grand country house paying tribute to the great gentlemen collectors of the period such as Sir Hans Sloane lovelondon london londoner londonpop london londonist londonart londontown london londonlove londonlife britishmuseum uk uk uktour visitlondon europe europetravel visitlondon

text: A new book by Barrister Geoffrey Robertson QC to be released in November argues for the Return of the Parthenon Marbles to Athens According to Stephen Fry the book proves beyond any reasonable doubt that the Parthenon Marbles belong back in Athens Elgin s heist prevents the modern world appreciating this ancient wonder created by the same people who gave us democracy philosophy and best of all comedy Other cultural crimes must also be redressed and in this important book Geoffrey Robertson shows why and how parthenon acropolis athens greece AcropolisMuseum BritishMuseum bringthemback reunitetheparthenon

name: 2019-10-01 22.32.10 2145107227707202080_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Just a few more from the British Museum Amit bha Buddha Buddha of Infinite Light carved of white marble and dedicated to the Chongguang temple in Hebei in composite statue with missing hands the right hand would have been raised in the gesture of fearlessness abhayamudra and the left hand lowered in the gesture of bestowal varadamudra the David Vases apparently the best known Chinese porcelains in the world due to their age these altar vases were produced in and presented as gifts to a temple on Xingyuan and are some of the earliest known blue and white ware They are referred to as the David Vases after the man who reunited the pair they had become separated over the ages Porcelain from Longquan China circa the tripod item in the front is modeled after an ancient incense burner so essentially was made as an antique reproduction at the time we purchased a reproduction of the reproduction many years ago in China continuing the tradition britishmuseum london
