text: Let s kick off Black History Month with this little chap a fierce faced rider who s sadly lost his horse He s probably about as tall as my thumb and cast from bronze which makes him more fragile than iron and thus more susceptible to damage his eyes are inlaid with silver to brighten them While his horse hasn t survived he still has his shield which he holds in front of him as he rides His other hand probably held a weapon originally Everything about him is the model of a Roman cavalryman from this tips of his boots to the folds of his cloak Why start here Because this sturdy little fellow isn t Italian or even British he s almost certainly Algerian or Moroccan We can tell because his hair and beard fall round his face in dreadlocks a look we also know from riders on Trajan s Column a copy of which you can see at the vamuseum if you re so minded This is undoubtably a representation of one of the famous Mauretanian riders employed by the Roman army across the Empire That includes Britain the Maurorum Aurelianorum a regiment of these soldiers was stationed on Hadrian s Wall in the s BC Our wee friend here hasn t got a specific date associated with him but we know he was found in London The Celts who lived in Britain during the Iron Age left no written histories of their civilisations The Romans were first to do that here which means that there have been Africans and their descendants living in Britain quite literally since records began UK bronze Roman period On display in gallery case Want more Don t miss my tour Remarkable Women at the British Museum now text: Darial Gorge c Painted by Ivan Aivazovsky Born July Feodosia Crimea Ukraine Died May Feodosia Crimea Ukraine Oil on canvas cm Famous Armenian painter who knew the sea and loved it sincerely Drawing ability of young Aivazovsky attracted the attention of A Kaznacheyev the town governor who helped Aivazovsky to enter the high school at Simferopol and in the St Petersburg Academy of Arts At the age of twenty he graduated from the Art Academy of St Petersburg with a gold medal At the age of he have already gained international fame During the period of Aivazovsky as a pensioner of the Academy of Arts spent time in Italy traveled to Germany France Spain and Holland He worked much and had many exhibitions meeting everywhere with success He painted a lot of marine landscapes which became very popular in Italy Aivazovsky s name is intricately bound with the sea Perhaps no one in Europe has painted the extraordinary beauty of the sea with so much feeling and expressiveness as Aivazovsky has writes V Adasov When in the artist returned to St Petersburg he was awarded the title of Academician and became attached to the General Naval Headquarters This allowed him to travel much with Russian fleet expeditions on different missions he visited Turkey Greece Egypt America From to he painted several canvases with naval warfare as the subject the pictures portrayed historical battles of the Russian Fleet Neither financial security nor life in Palace interested him He returned to his native land built a workplace home on the seashore and until the last days of his life dedicates himself to the work that he loved Aivazovsky left more than pictures Most of his works are world famous museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado text: This could be a contemporary British tabloid cartoon of Boris Johnson and Emmanuel Macron but actually this is a satirical etching from published by William Holland Titled Britannia weighing the Fate of Europe or John Bull too heavy for Buonaparte the print depicts the statuesque figure of Britannia holding the scales of Justice The diminutive Napoleon is no match to the portly well fed Englishman John Bull who tips the scales to Britain s benefit The speech buble for John Bull says A Conceited little Boaster to pretend to be weigh d against me does he think I eat Beef and pudding for nothing Image The Trustees of the British Museum prints etching satire humour britain politics britishhistory britishpolitics history napoleon napoleonicwars johnbull nineteenthcentury thcentury thcenturyart art arthistory britishmuseum

name: 2019-10-02 22.59.58 2145845997211975248_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Nello and Patrasche A Dog of Flanders Nello and Patrasche is without a doubt the most beautiful story about Flanders the Dutch speaking part of the little country Belgium in Europe Nello is a young orphan who has an incredible friendship with a street dog named Patrasche Both of them are homeless and they stay a lot in the cathedral of Antwerp where they admire the works of Rubens the world famous painter After a series of mishaps both day on Christmas Eve from starvation and the freezing temperature The cathedral which was the only home they have ever known becomes the spot where they take their farewell from this cruel world together as always like the undivided friends they were It is perhaps one of the saddest Christmas stories in the whole world but people are touched by this story even until today Based on a true story The story unfolds in the towns of Antwerp and Hoboken in Flanders The Flemish artist Batist Vermeulen was asked by the city of Antwerp to sculpt a statue in remembrance and celebration of this story and the protagonists In the endearing statue was erected in the shadow of the cathedral and is a tribute to Nello and Patrasche who really lived and died there but it is also a reminder that there is nothing worse than loneliness and that there is even in the st century ugly things like poverty and abandoned people in our societies This atypical Christmas story has captured the hearts of many people especially in Japan where this story is the most told story to the youth The mix of true friendship unconditional love and a tragic end is what great stories are all about The artist Vermeulen has captured not only the spirit of the story but also the atmosphere of Flemish traditions Historical evidence proves that both Nello and Patrasche were real The people of Antwerp have closed them in their hearts for centuries The statue is a fitting modern structure to an ancient story and it shows that emotions are timeless The pavement that is upon them as a blanket is symbolic of the city of Antwerp covering them with their respect and love Big stories are sometimes found in little corners

text: Fashion Gardens Garden Museum This critically acclaimed and extensively reviewed exhibition at the Garden Museum in Lambeth explored the relationship between gardening and fashion Curated by the historian and writer Nicola Shulman historian writer and curator of the exhibition Jointly organised by the Garden Museum and British Vogue the exhibition featured works by designers such as Valentino Alexander McQueen Philip Treacy and Christopher Bailey as well as a number of remarkable loans from the British Museum National Gallery and the V A I think it is a miracle what you have achieved in such a short time on such an exceedingly short shoestring The show looks very elegant coherent and smart Nicola Shulman londonatelierarchitects instadesign ic architecture archicage architecturegram architecture hunter thinkingarchitecture littleblackbox ny critday studioofblo photooftheday instagood exhibitiondesign temporaryexhibition temporaryinstallation britishvogue Valentino AlexanderMcQueen PhilipTreacy christopherbailey britishmuseum nationalgallery victoriaandalbertmuseum furniture modern detail propertydevelopment property propertyinvestment realestate

text: I found this little copper alloy acorn last week on the Thames foreshore Even though it s small I think it s could be a button perhaps more decorative than practical The shank seems to have worn through which is probably how it got lost Acorns have been popular decorative motifs since at least Roman times a quick wizz through the Portable Antiquities Scheme Database confirmed this with the number of buttons mounts brooches spoons buckles strap ends that feature them and I found a few bits of th century Geman stoneware in my own collection with acorns and oak leaves moulded into them Oaks are still one of our most common species of tree and have a wise and magical quality about them Since they are usually the tallest trees in the landscape they are often hit by lightening which may be why they were considered sacred to Zeus Jupiter and the Celtic Dagda each of which ruled over thunder and lightning Druids also revered the oak practising their rituals in oak groves and honouring the mistletoe that grows in its branches Ancient kings and Roman Emperors wore crowns of oak leaves and during the time of Oliver Cromwell couples were wed under oak trees Oaks provided firewood and valuable hardwood for furniture barrels house beams and ships The lower branches could be harvested as food for livestock oak galls were used to make ink tannin in the bark was used to tan leather and acorns could be ground up to make flour for bread or used to fatten up pigs Leaves bark and acorns were also thought to have many medicinal properties including a cure for diarrhoea inflammation and kidney stones It s said old spoons often had acorn finials as protection from the bloody flux so perhaps this little acorn was an added talisman against disease LondonMudlark Mudlark Mudlarking

text: El Gran Atrio del British Museum fue algo que me sorprendi much simo Lo hab a visto en fotos y me parec a imponente pero estar all hizo que fuera m s brutal a n El edificio del medio es la Sala de Lectura fue inicialmente la biblioteca del museo y fue inaugurada en Escritores como Conan Doyle o Bram Stoker acud an all a leer En se construy el Gran Atrio que rodea la Sala de Lectura y el patio interior del museo pas a ser la plaza p blica cubierta m s grande de Europa Eso demuestra la inmensidad del lugar Las propias estancias la propia arquitectura de los lugares d nde se encuentran estos museos me ha sorprendido gratamente Merece la pena visitarlo no solo por su contenido si no tambi n por sus formas

name: 2019-10-04 00.36.32 2146619377536109936_britishmuseum.jpg
text: The Cornish Coast Painted by Dame Laura Knight Born August Long Eaton Derbyshire England Died July London England aged Oil on canvas x cm Location National Museum of Wales One of the leading female artists of the twentieth century The youngest of the three daughters of Charles and Charlotte Johnson Her father abandoned the family not long after her birth and Knight grew up amid financial problems Charlotte Johnson taught part time at the Nottingham School of Art and managed to have Knight enrolled as an artisan student there paying no fees aged just At the age of fifteen and still a student herself Knight took over her mother s teaching duties when Charlotte was diagnosed with cancer and became seriously ill Laura met one of the most promising students Harold Knight then aged and determined that the best method of learning was to copy Harold s technique They became friends and married in changing her surname from Johnson At first they lived in an artist s colony in Staithes North Yorkshire until moving to Newlyn Cornwall in where they became leading members of the Newlyn School of Artists In she moved to St John s Wood which was to be the base for the remainder of her life Laura was known for painting amidst the world of the theatre and ballet in London and for being a war artist during the Second World War She was also greatly interested in and inspired by marginalised communities and individuals including Gypsies and circus performers In Harold Knight died at Colwall the couple had been married fifty eight years Laura died in aged three days before a large exhibition of her work opened at the Nottingham Castle Art Gallery and Museum museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum name: 2019-10-04 13.59.05 2147023311048220192_britishmuseum.jpg
text: La Femme au Chat c Painted by Edouard Manet Born January Paris France Died April Paris France aged Oil on canvas x cm Location Tate Museum London Manet had an upper class upbringing but also led a bohemian life and was driven to scandalize the French Salon public with his disregard for academic conventions and his strikingly modern images of urban life He has long been associated with the Impressionists he was certainly an important influence on them and he learned much from them himself However in recent years critics have acknowledged that he also learned from the Realism and Naturalism of his French contemporaries and even from th century Spanish painting This twin interest in Old Masters and contemporary Realism gave him the crucial foundation for his revolutionary approach Manet s modernity lies above all in his eagerness to update older genres of painting by injecting new content or by altering the conventional elements He did so with an acute sensitivity to historical tradition and contemporary reality This was also undoubtedly the root cause of many of the scandals he provoked He is credited with popularizing the technique of alla prima painting Rather than build up colors in layers Manet would immediately lay down the hue that most closely matched the final effect he sought The approach came to be used widely by the Impressionists who found it perfectly suited to the pressures of capturing effects of light and atmosphere whilst painting outdoors His loose handling of paint and his schematic rendering of volumes led to areas of flatness in his pictures In the artist s day this flatness may have suggested popular posters or the artifice of painting as opposed to its realism Today critics see this quality as the first example of flatness in modern art Manet continued to paint portraits of women still lifes landscapes and flowers even from his sickbed Succumbing to a nervous disorder most likely from tertiary syphilis Manet died a horrible death after having been reduced to a wheelchair from gangrene and even losing his leg

text: Have you ever noticed the hundreds of tiny works of art you re treading on as you cross the Millennium Bridge They are the work of Ben Wilson outsider artist who paints on the chewing gum that s stuck to the bridge It s got him into a bit of trouble with the police in the past but because he s not actually defacing private property just painting rubbish he s not actually breaking the law First he melts the chewing gum with a small blow torch then he shapes it to the desired size sprays it with lacquer and heats it up again to transform it into a solid disc I ve been stopping to chat to Ben for years and he s kindly painted me my own piece of mudlarking gum Ben s art bypasses bureaucracy and the controlled spaces of galleries and similar institutions and this weekend he is opening his Gum Trail Join him at pm on Sat th Oct at the St Paul s end of the bridge LondonMudlark Mudlark Mudlarking

text: The change in seasons brings us much cooler temperatures more damp days and higher quantities of rain as well as much darker and shorter days Hydration has been known as a key to wellness and health in any season especially in the colder weather Drinking tea can help you stay hydrated as well as keeping you warm The tea of October goes to Soothing Indian Herbal Infusion which has a lovely warming effect on the body Its taste is a complex infusion of spices combined with sweetness from liquorice root and rounded off with floral notes of rose petals The infusion also has sweet and spicy aromas with a flowery accent It s a wonderfully fresh cup to start your Autumn tea camelliasteahouse britishmuseum teaparty teapartytheme londontearoom londontea londonteatime afternoontealondon afternoontea englishtea traditionaltea teatime teaobsessed rosetea teaholic tealover healthydrinks herbaltea visitlondon explorelondon

text: MCM Dinnerware spotted Town and Country and Well of the Sea both by acclaimed designers Eva Zeisel and American designer William Craig McBirney for Shenango China of Syracuse Zeisel s work is made for Red Wing pottery of Minnesota She was asked to produce an informal inexpensive service to boldly modern The result was this collection which took its name form a popular magazine Town and Country Eva s love of inventive humorous and practical forms is obvious with her different choice of colors which could be mixed and matched easily Her forms are organic McBirney s plates cups and saucers are also distinct because of its spindly linear construction a familiar feature of post war Art midcenturymodern midcentury evazeisel williammcbirney britishmuseum midcenturydining midcenturydecor mcmpottery

text: Pottery shard found by Klay on the Thames a few days ago Could it be Madam Blondin Selina Young who traversed a metre rope across the Thames from Battersea to Cremorne Gardens in Augst She performed the feat five times to audiences of around people taking about seven minutes to make each crossing A newspaper report of the time stated her performance is apparently fraught with little danger for she crosses the rope with an ease freedom and self possession that is truly astounding But tradgedy struck a year later when she suffered a serious fall while crossing a highwire at Highbury Barn She had already traversed the line in a suit of armour and pushing a wheelbarrow and was crossing while clutching a balancing pole loaded with lit fireworks They exploded asymmetrically threw her off balance and she fell metres to the ground breaking her neck and thigh The accident left her a mangled cripple and she apparently never performed again Londonmudlark Mudlark mudlarking

text: Halloween is not far away To get into the mood here s an appropriate satire originally published by William Holland on October Titled Resurrection Men this etching with a hint of aquatint depicts a group of grave robbers spooked by an unhappy looking ghost who holds a bone maybe one of his own in his hand The occupation of resurrection men became notorious in the th century when fascination with anatomy grew and many scientists and anatomists needed fresh cadavers for their research The primary way of acquiring corpses was by using the unwanted cadavers by the poor homeless or unclaimed but there were persistent rumours that on occasion grave robbing was resorted to in order to keep the fresh flow of research material Subsequently a whole new profession emerged and these resurrection men often in competition with each other took more and more risks to turn a profit from delivering more and more cadavers Image The Trustees of the British Museum prints etching satire humour ghost halloween october eighteenthcentury thcentury thcenturyart art arthistory britishmuseum

text: The autumn term is galloping I m leading four different courses at two separate universities Two of those courses Black British Music Exploring Identity Through Sound and Breaking America Exploring the Value of British Music National Identity Culture via International Success provide space for several field trips We visit a variety of venues absorbing the passionate expertise of musicians historians to fully grasp the real world consequences of the constructions of racial social identities the imperial pursuit colonisation of nations the transportation and enslavement of Africans the oppression of African indigeneity the use of cultural facets OF African indigeneity of people of natural resources for reputational benefit in the West These trips ALL relate to music The international view of a nation propagandised to how the Other musically respond to being Othered BY that nation is approached through visits to the metronomes mso Pan Yard where students play Trinidad Tobago s national instrument tangibly exploring the steel drum s position within anti colonial expression of musicality measured against more established formally recognised instruments We also take part in AliceProctor s uncomfortablearttour at the BritishMuseum extracting the truth from the imperial over simplifications subjectivities and omissions accompanying imperial artefacts on permanent display in one of the UK s most popular museums What these items foreign works of art worship clothing tools labour war many demanded back say in this official and popular space about racialised gendered and classed narrative inter national power and the recontextualisation of history to suit those positions reflects the enduring nature of contemporary misrepresentation historic racialised classed gendered institutionalised When my Breaking America students visit the Royal Albert Hall glance out unto the Albert Memorial they re looking at a tribute w carved global Others in subjugation text: LONDON ARCHITECTURE The British Museum Robert Smirke Foster Partners At the heart of this cultural institution is the Great Court the largest and arguably most extraordinary covered courtyard in Europe Added in consider this proof that the architecture of one era really can be enhanced by another And if the promise of a vast two acre two century old Greek Revivalist masterpiece isn t enough it s topped by a hypnotic tessellated glass roof Architecture turns artwork with geometric shadow patterns cast across the light filled space Explore the museum s renowned archive of artefacts or just sit back in what is one of central London s most serene meeting spots An extract from our new photo book An Opinionated Guide to London Architecture which takes readers on a tour around London via the best buildings Light of exhibition is on at Coal Drops Yard until October Publisher hoxtonminipressText sujataburman biscott iPhotography taranwilkhuPR smithandbaxterArchitect fosterandpartners londonarchitecture hoxtonminipress wallpapermag architect booklaunch archilovers architecturelovers architecture archiporn londonist architexture architectureguide designlovers architecturephotography architektur britishmuseum londonlife londonmuseum normanfoster normanfoserarchitecture fosterandpartners robertsmirke thebritishmuseum revivalist geometry architecturedetails lightandshade thegreatcourt

text: The Guitarist c Painted by Jean Baptiste Greuze Born August Tournus France Died March Louvre Paris France aged Oil on canvas x cm His early life is obscure but he studied painting in Lyons and appeared in Paris about He entered the Royal Academy as a student and worked with Charles Joseph Natoire a prominent decorative painter During the s Greuze achieved a significant reputation with his sentimental paintings of peasants or lower class people seen in humble surroundings and in the midst of theatrically emotional family situations In Greuze was admitted to the academy as a genre painter Ambitious to become a member of the academy as a history painter which was a higher rank he was so angered by his admission as only a genre painter that he refused to show his paintings at the academy s exhibitions the Salons But by that time he was already famous and could afford to ignore the Salons French painting during the th century was dominated by the rococo style Rococo painting was aristocratic in nature elegant and sensuous stylistically it depended upon soft colors complex surfaces refined textures free brushwork and asymmetrical compositions based upon the interplay of curved lines and masses Produced for highly sophisticated patrons rococo painting concentrated on aristocratic diversions decorative portraits mythological and allegorical themes frequently treated in a playful or erotic manner and idyllic pastoral scenes Greuze s pretentiously moralizing rustic dramas constituted a reaction against rococo frivolity in art by appealing to emotion they were also a revolt against the emphasis placed upon reason and science by the philosophers of the Enlightenment the intellectual movement that pervaded the first half of the th century The rising importance of the middle class and of middle class morality also played a part in the success of Greuze s cottage genre Greuze survived the French Revolution but his fame did not He died in Paris on March in poverty and obscurity

text: Hi followers I ve been a bit quiet on here since wrapping up season of Past Matters life has been a bit busy but this podcast is never far from my mind and plotting the Christmas special and season for next year is top of my priority list this afternoon What else are Sundays for right Anyway I thought I d take the opportunity to introduce myself properly in case you were wondering about who the muppet asking the experts questions is So my name is Ploy Radford I m years old and live in London I used to be a full time journalist but now I do a bit of freelance writing around the day job of working in PR Obviously I love history I have a degree in classics from Cambridge Uni and the history modules were my favourite part Horses reading eating and travel are also passions I suppose shopping is a guilty hobby too this photo was taken in the British Museum exhibition gift shop history and shopping heaven Do say hi in the comments and let me know which episodes you enjoyed and suggested venues for next season historygirls historygeek podcastlife newpodcastalert historylovers pastmatterspodcast historypodcast arthistory britishmuseum furryhats freelancewriter podcaster

text: Yellow Tree Red Barn c Painted by Irina Rybakova Born Vyshny Volochok Russia Oil on canvas x in Location Grenning Gallery Irina Rybakova is a famous Russian master of landscape The image of the Russian village and the village worker are her dearest subjects Her art is appreciated in museums and collections both in Russia and abroad Irina worked as part of the artistic group Academica dacha in Vyshny Volochek the oldest and well known creative base of the Union of Artists of the Russian Federation In she entered Kostroma a historic city department of Artists Union in Russia Promotes the contemporary realistic school in art in mass media Image of the Russian village and the village worker are her most dear subjects and does not like landscapes without humans museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting tree irinarybakova vyshnyvolochok russia artinfluencer grenninggallery kostroma yourarttimes

text: Today we are on Acropolis in Athens Greece You can see here a part of a temple called Erechtheion The building itself has an original construction As it was built on slope the west and north sides are about m ft lower than the south and east sides The main role here is played by columns called Caryatids These are the most famous and the most often copied ones however the concept apparently had come from Middle East where the columns had been made as mithological creatures of women s heads Here you see only replicas You can find five original ones in Acropolis Museum and the sixth one is held by British Museum caryatids caryatid erechtheion acropolis athens greece acropolismuseum britishmuseum ancient ancientarchitecture architecture archi archilovers

text: Spent some time in the British Museum in London this week which houses an astounding collection of world artefacts thanks to the extent of the British Empire Here are objects that completely captured my attention a year old flint bull s head from Egypt a deity symbol of power and virility an year old shamanic deer mask made from a large red deer stag from Star Carr in England and a year old Neolithic polished axe made from tuff from the Lake District I was able to hold the axe and feel a connection to the person who made and used it but even to be in the presence of these other glassed in artefacts was a powerful visceral experience primitiveskills ancestralskills britishmuseum rewilding prehistoricarchaeology experimentalarchaeology stoneage flintknapping mesolithicdeermask

text: Welwyn Garden City Hertfordshire Reconstruction of the richest Iron Age burial found in Britain Discovered at Welwyn Garden City Hertfordshire st Century BCE The burial was that of an important man whose body had been wrapped in a bear skin and cremated The burnt bones were placed in a heap on the floor of the grave The large burial vault was filled with numerous pots metal vessels and other offerings The burial also contained wooden bowls and buckets a straw mat and other organic materials which have long since perished Most of the grave goods are native but the wine amphorae and silver cup are iItalian while the platters and large flagon were made in Gaul Wine amphorae are only found in burials north of the Thames The grave dates from late in the first century BC midway between the expeditions of Julius Caesar BCE and the invasion of the Emperor Claudius CE archaeologicalmuseum archaeologia archaeology archaeologylife historylovers archaeologylove museum museum lovers pottery history britishhistory england ironage burial britishironage britishmuseum storiantica london historia museumsaroundtheworld welwyngarden archaeologist ancientcivilization artefacts igworldclub archaeology

name: 2019-10-08 14.59.45 2149952944655681815_britishmuseum.jpg
text: Cueva de las Manos Cueva de las Manos is a cave which is located in the heart of Patagonia in the province of Santa Cruz Argentina The name can be translated from Spanish as The Cave of Hands In a monk discovered this unusual cave in the gorge of the river Pinturas Rio Pinturas Then he couldn t even imagine that this was the oldest and perhaps the most sensational cave rock paintings in the world Later in a professor of archeology Carlos Gradin thanks to his researches glorified the Cave of Hands to the whole world However he was concerned about the safety of the original appearance of this discovery In the Cueva de las Manos was included into the UNESCO World Heritage List Thus it has become one of the most important attractions of Argentina Scientists say that these unique cave paintings were made about thousand years ago They were created using stencils and natural dyes such as white clay iron oxide and manganese Thus the prints acquired the purple green and blue colors The remarkable fact is that the same colors were used during the funeral rites The ritual of creating handprints by the natural colors was a peculiar custom which is considered to be a rite of initiation This is a series of caves speckled with similar patterns Their length amounts km In general the drawings are divided into three groups according to their age and style There are more than prints of human hands in a life size as well as images of animals resembling deer and camels human figures and hunting scenes It is worth mentioning that only prints are traces of right hands The cave is not very big in size so probably people came here to relax after hunting and conducted various rituals Since the Cave of Hands is hidden from the human eye in a deep gorge of the river it s pretty hard to get here The cave is situated in a deserted place without any settlements

text: Next Thursday th October I am running the first of my autumn London walks This first amble is in Bloomsbury a part of London I absolutely adore at this time of year Our walk will take us down quiet Georgian streets and around the British Museum pictured here We will see the imposing Art Deco Senate House the Ministry of Information in Orwell s and a famous green cab shelter We ll visit Coram Fields and wander through some of London s prettiest squares I ve specifically set the walk to start at pm to make the most of the magical twilight as we take our walk At this time of year the plane trees are resplendent and create a network of cosseting canopies over the garden squares and in the early evening the curtains are left undrawn offering us glimpses of Georgian drawing rooms in the fading light If you d like to come there are just two places left All details in my bio Oh and we ll be ending our walk with a drink in a cosy London pub Just the place to be on an atmospheric October evening bleakhouseexperiences londonbylondoners bloomsbury britishmuseum

text: The Great Court of The British Museum in London Does it look too clinical or is it interesting architecture I m in the second camp I know it s not cool to have the non square thing on Insta but the full wide view is the only way to do this justice The British Museum is dedicated to human history art and culture It has a permanent collection of over million works and is among the largest and most comprehensive in the world It was established in covers sq ft sq metres over galleries It was the first public national gallery in the world and incredibly remains free of charge to enter It is not without controversy Elgin Marbles and the Rosetta Stone are endlessly debated whether they should return to their countries of origin The Great Court pictured here is the central quadrangle now there s a word It is dedicated to the Queen Elizabeth II and is the largest covered square in Europe It s very easy to get lost in here and spend a long time finding the exact location where you promised you d meet your husband just saying

text: Congratulations to britishmuseum for another thought provoking exhibition Inspired by the East explores the impact that the Islamic world has had on Western art from to the current day The show uses artefacts including art ceramics photography glass and clothing to highlight a centuries old tradition of influence from East to West and ends with works of four artists working today exploring the idea of Orientalism including this print reimagining th century harem paintings by the Moroccan artist Lalla Essaydi The exhibition opens on October and runs until January A companion book is available to purchase https www museumbookstore com products inspired by the east how the islamic world influenced western art

text: Because I was often asked what is a Triglyph here we are Triglyph means in Greek Three tris channels glyphes and it is part of the Doric frieze together with a Metope Some archaeologists say that its shape come from the union of three wooden planks that support the roof of the temple Others say it comes from the stylization of a tripod A typical Triglyph is made up of a upper horizontal part called Capital the three vertical channels called Glyphs an horizontal line called Taenia which is often decorated with a Maeander design the lower part called Regula which is followed by drop shaped small parts called Guttae All those parts are putted together following precise geometric relationships as the Golden Section one I hope you enjoyed my little description doric doricorder classicalarchitecture classicalart classicalarchaeology triglyph triglyphs metope doricfrieze dorictemple parthenonmarbles parthenon reunitetheparthenonmarbles britishmuseumlondon britishmuseum archaeostoryteller greektemples acropolis eustacepalladinos eustacepalladinos com

text: One of the historical figures that really impacts fragrance history is the Roman emperor Constantine the Great He moved the seat of Christianity to modern day Istanbul Constantinople he called it not a modest man and set up generous budgets for aromatics in the churches he was having built Before him Christians largely associated scent with Greek Egyptian and Roman style paganism and idolatry After him they started to associate good scent with godliness Indirectly it s thanks to Constantine that we have a tradition of burning aromatics in Catholic churches Here we see a censer from around AD right during or after his reign scenthistory istanbulnotconstantinople christianity britishmuseum perfumehistory history

text: Too many gems in this brilliant and thought provoking britishmuseum show How the East Influenced the West to know what to post But here are a few picks first Palestinian artist Raedah Saadeh Who Will Make me Real challenges idealised notions of the Orientalist Odalisque by wrapping herself in newspapers referring to the politics of the Middle East and through her daring gaze then the Qajar ruler Mozaffar al din Shah whose portrait was influenced by European styles of photography and lastly a contemporary Turkish video installation inspired by a C work The show is all about how we see the other and how the two sides have dialogued with one another over the centuries albukhary orientalism

text: INAUGURACI N DE MUSEO SOBRE CASTILLO EN PONFERRADATodo a punto INAUGURACI N Mi rcoles Capic a del a o PONS FERR ART El puente en el Arte Un pintor universal cada a o coincidiendo con sus Aniversarios en total hasta el a o del MILENARIO expondr n sus puentes Santalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO Los tres primeros museos ya se han inaugurado en Lapuebla de Labarca San Juan de la Mata y Madrid El pr ximo ser el de Ponferrada OPENING OF MUSEUM ON CASTLE IN PONFERRADAEverything on point OPENING Wednesday Capic a of the year PONS FERR ART The bridge in Art A universal painter every year coinciding with his Anniversaries in total until the year of the MILENARY will exhibit their bridges Santalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose purpose is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM The first three museums have already opened in Lapuebla de Labarca San Juan de la Mata and Madrid The next will be Ponferrada reinasofiamuseum museodelprado caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma museedorsay louvre met salvadordalimuseum britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi galleriaborghese gettymuseum yaleartgallery sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

text: Manga la mostra al British MuseumSecondo alcuni i Manga sono robe per bambini o al contrario sono diseducativi Al British Museum la pensano diversamente tanto che l si da poco svolta la pi grande mostra fuori dal Giappone interamente dedicata ai Manga I Manga sono una forma d arte narrativa visiva che diventata un fenomeno multimediale globale raccontando storie con temi di vario genere ambientati in mondi reali o immaginari Si tratta di uno storytelling coinvolgente che funziona attraverso le immagini che regnano sovrane I caratteri giapponesi con cui scritta la parola Manga possono essere tradotti con Immagini in rivolta o Immagini illimitate C meno dipendenza dal testo e la narrativa viene creata attraverso il disegno di linee espressive e lo sviluppo visivo dei singoli personaggi la qualit visivamente coinvolgente del manga che lo rende cos unico e popolare Si pensa che i primi esempi di Manga siano nati in Giappone intorno alla prima met del XIII secolo sotto forma di rotoli di pergamena detti emaki rotoli illustrati che spesso rappresentavano caricature di personaggi umani o di animali antropomorfi come rane o conigli Sono stati poi alcuni artisti del XVIII secolo a coniare la parola Manga che all epoca poteva essere tradotta con Disegni bizzarri e divertenti I primi fumetti giapponesi nascono negli anni Venti del Novecento attraverso la pubblicazione di strisce di cartoni animati seriali su riviste e giornali Ma i Manga almeno quelli che oggi conosciamo fecero la prima comparsa nel nell edizione di Osaka del quotidiano Shokokumin shinbun dove vennero pubblicate alcune strisce del diario di Ma chan ad opera di un giovanissimo disegnatore di nome Osamu Tezuka manga mangaexhibition britishmuseum

text: A must visit when in London britishmuseum I can t believe this was my first time to visit this museum though I d been to London so many times This is part of the Assyrians exhibition The mighty Assyrian empire began as the small city state of Ashur in what is now the north eastern region of Iraq Visitors entered palaces through massive gateways flanked by colossal human headed winged bulls called lamassu that protected the King from dangerous supernatural forces In light of what is happening nowadays in Iraq it is imperative that we learn the vast and rich history it breeds It used to be the cradle of civilisations so let s work together and help where we can I ve put a link in my bio to sign a petition by unhcr iraq to help the Iraqi people letsTalkRealWorldIssues theCelebrationProject

text: I spent Easter with family in Kent One lazy day I and my Niece decided to visit Central London and do a solo tour which included galleries stadiums and I made sure the British museum was on the list It wasn t my first time but museums are my favourite And I wouldn t pass up the opportunity to visit the Africa exhibit and the Benin Mask By the way the recreation for The Black Panther was almost spot on The knives exhibit I still have so many unedited pictures of the day The postcard shows the view of the museum roof The interior is twice as beautiful with all the natural light On the same day we passed through King s Cross Station I basically lived there and can t count how many times I passed through On this day I decided to finally live my Harry Potter fantasy and posed for a picture at Platform I went to the shop to pick up the printed photo and saw it would cost me about I bought a postcard instead AnnaTakesShotsLS Postcards

text: Girl in a Field c Painted by Ludwig Knaus Born October Wiesbaden Germany Died December Berlin Germany Location Hermitage Museum St Petersburg Studied from to under Sohn and Schadow in D sseldorf His early works like The Gamblers in the D sseldorf Gallery are in the manner of that school being dark and heavy in color This deficiency was remedied by study at Paris whither he went in and enrolled as a pupil of Thomas Couture In his Morning after the Kermess received the second gold Medal of the Salon and made him a celebrated painter Except for a year s study in Italy he remained in Paris until His chief works of this period include The Golden Wedding The Baptism and The Promenade purchased for the Luxembourg From to he practiced at Berlin producing such works as Boys Playing Cards Looking for a Bride and His Highness on His Travels The next eight years of his life saw the production of much of his best work including The Children s Festival In Great Distress and The Village Prince From to he was professor at the Royal Prussian Academy Berlin continuing to reside in that city until his death He was a member of the Berlin Munich and many other academies an Officer of the Legion of Honor and a Knight of the Prussian Order Pour le M rite Possibly his most famous work is Girl in a Field Engravings of his works were especially popular among the German peasantry Ludwig Knaus s work has been offered at auction multiple times with realized prices ranging from USD to USD depending on the size and medium of the artwork Since the record price for this artist at auction is USD for Charity sold at Christie s New York in The artist died in museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting field ludwigknaus wiesbaden berlin yourarttimes

text: Inspired By The East How The Islamic World Influenced Western Art Exhibition British Museum am pm Charting the fascinating history of cultural and artistic interactions between East and West this exhibition explores the impact the Islamic world has had on Western art for centuries Artistic exchange between East and West has a long and intertwined history and the exhibition picks these stories up from the th century following cultural interactions that can still be felt today Objects from Europe North America the Middle East and North Africa highlight a centuries old tradition of influence and exchange from East to West The diverse selection of objects includes ceramics photography glass jewellery and clothing as well as contemporary art showcasing how artistic exchange influenced a variety of visual and decorative arts The exhibition concludes with a st century perspective through the eyes of four female artists from the Middle East and North Africa who continue to question and subvert the idea of Orientalism in their work and explore the subject of Muslim female identity The show takes a deeper look at the art movement of Orientalism specifically the way in which North Africa and the Middle East were represented as lands of beauty and intrigue especially in European and North American art Often blurring the lines between fantasy and reality Orientalist art reached its heyday in the mid s as Europeans and North Americans were looking overseas to fundamentally learn more about other cultures but its popularity had faded by the s with the decline of the British Empire More information via link in bio Visit Bounce for more London events www bounce london islamicart britishmuseum whatsonlondon exhibitonslondon artlondon bounce

text: Today is World Mental Health Day and I have thought long and hard about a suitable post In the end I decided to just give you the river my healer and soulmate my confidante and saviour When I was by the river I was somewhere else disconnected from the city and a world away from my problems It was my escape from people work awkward situations even sometimes from myself It was where I went to forget about my failing relationship and my unfulfilling jobs it healed my broken heart helped me to make sense of the senseless and threw a watery arm around my shoulders when life became too much Sometimes just a stolen halfhour was enough Other times I walked beside it for miles casting my problems into the retreating tide telling it my secrets Mudlarking Lost and Found on the River Thames by Lara Maiklem LondonMudlark Mudlark Mudlarking mudlarkingbook

text: Snettisham Norfolk Snettisham torc torcs Iceni The Snettisham Hoard The Snettisham Treasure is a series of discoveries of Iron Age precious metal found in Snettisham Norfolk between and The hoard consists of around metal torc fragments and over complete torcs stiff metal necklaces dating from BCE The torcs are made from twisted strands of solid gold and silver wire and had been deliberately buried in a pit after several years of heavy use One hypothesis suggests the deliberate destruction of valuable items was a form of votive offering Though its origins are unknown the hoard is of a high enough quality to have been royal treasure of the Iceni a Britonnic tribe of Iron Age Britain archaeologicalmuseum archaeologia archaeology archaeologylife historylovers archaeologylove museum museum lovers gold ancientgreece ironage torcs preciousmetal storiantica britain historia museumsaroundtheworld archaeologist mythology britonnic artefacts britisharchaeology britishmuseum snettishamhoard hoard

text: Resonance from the past British MuseumElgin was a lover of art and antiquities Concerned about damage being done to important artworks in the temples of Greece he asked permission of the Sublime Porte to have artists measure sketch and copy important pieces of sculpture and architectural detail for posterity An outcry arose over the affair and Elgin was assailed for rapacity vandalism and dishonesty in hauling the Grecian treasures to London The Greek government has frequently demanded the return of the marbles but the British Museum has not acceded and the issue remains controversial

name: 2019-10-10 22.55.37 2151642014920546243_britishmuseum.jpg
text: The Waterloo Helmet is an example of a ceremonial horned helmet from Celtic La Tene culture The helmet was originally decorated with pieces of red glass and would have been even more visually striking when it was made It is impractical for use in combat and was probably only used for ceremonial purposes possibly in processions or parades The bronze helmet was made c BCE and was found in the Thames River near the Waterloo Bridge England It is the only example of an Iron Age horned helmet to be found in Europe and the only Iron Age helmet to be found in southern England The Waterloo Helmet is on display in the British Museum in London Image by the British Museum

text: withrepost garlandmagazine Oblivion by Sheraz Faisal Sheraz Faisal s practice as a designer and fine artist overlap to each other and he showed an enigmatic vocabulary of visuals that are sensuous and edgy His approach to his subject matter is always very minimal and refined Bullet is an object of destruction a universal notion to show masculinity and power He wanted to negate this idea and convert it into something ornate object for everyday life His fascination kept him going to discover the symbolism and taboos attached to a bullet In the last ten years the war against the terror brought Pakistan into limelight and western media around the world focused to sell the stories of Pakistan either true or false bullets or veil the negative image projected of the country always bothered him Sheraz was compelled and passionate to see through the haze and do his bit to let the world see the creative side of the nation He started collecting empty fired bullet shells to make very simple pair of earrings by adding tiny semi precious stones or engraving roses on it His fellow artist admired his creativity and encouraged him Soon ALIEL discovered and got him on board to get a conscious and professional attitude towards his work and manufacturing Oblivion was created using copper fired bullet shells gold plated with K yellow gold pink tourmaline white pearls and a halo of diamonds added a new character to the piece In our current issue Asad Hayee documents a project with Sheraz Faisal to create jewellery interpretations of artworks SherazFaisal Pakistanjewellery Lahore garlandmag thestans diamonds jewelrydesigner fashiondesigner textiledesign furnituredesign salimahashmi vogue barber luxuryjewelry finejewelry ink menwithtattoos hautejoaillerie oneofakind instadaily history inked visualart hoscos britishmuseum fashiondiaries milano lifeofadventures bnulive alieljewellers pifd

text: Momia de la mala suerte El portal web de National Geographic ha publicado un interesante art culo sobre la supuesta maldici n de una momia que se encuentra en el Museo Brit nico de Londres En realidad no se trata de una momia sino de una tapa de ata d egipcia que perteneci a una mujer de alto rango posiblemente una sacerdotisa de Am n Ra a la cual se le atribuyen m ltiples desgracias La m s sonada es la de haber sido la causante del hundimiento del Titanic El ata d de metros consiste en una cubierta antropomorfa repleta de jerogl ficos pintada de vivos colores tallada en madera y yeso y data hacia finales de la dinast a XXI a C El objeto fue bautizado hace a os comoThe Unlucky Mummy la momia de la mala suerte a pesar de que en realidad tal momia no existe Pero por qu se le puso tan nefasto nombre Parece ser que a esta sacerdotisa se le atribuyen las mil y una desgracias relacionadas con sus sucesivos propietarios y sobre quienes intentaron contar la historia de sus maldades La leyenda m s impresionante sin duda es la cuenta que el sarc fago viajaba a bordo del Titanic y fue el causante del hundimiento del famoso transatl ntico Asimismo seg n algunos rumores llevaba un amuleto en su cabeza que rezaba as Despierta de tu postraci n y el rayo de tus ojos aniquilar a todos aquellos que quieran adue arse de ti Evidentemente en torno a la cubierta del ata d de esta mujer se mezclan todo tipo de informaciones algunas verdaderas otras rumores y la mayor a aut nticos disparates Sin embargo los invito a leer el reportaje completo pues es una interesante historia que vale la pena conocer Fuente https www nationalgeographic com es historia curiosa momia mala suerte amp Imagen tomada de https elpais com cultura actualidad amp html egipto egypt momia mummy maldicion curse antiguoegipto ancientegypt britishmuseum legends leyendas egiptologia egiptofaraonico

text: Opened today at the British Museum BritishMuseum Lalla Essaydi lallaessaydi in Inspired by the East How the Islamic World Influenced Western Art Right off the heels of Frieze Friezeartfair week in London the excitement in the art world continues with this compelling show co curatored by Julia Tugwell JuliaTugwell and Olivia Threlkeld OliviaThrelkeld sponsored by Standard Chartered Bank stanchart and organized with Islamic Arts Museum Malaysia islamicartsmuseummalaysia The show examines how European and North American visual arts have been inspired by the Islamic world for centuries Known as Orientalism this representation of the East in Western art often blurred the line between fantasy and reality Featured in the show is photographer Lalla Essaydi who reimagines the harem paintings of th Century Orientalism to show women as active agents rather than passive objects subjected to the voyeuristic imaginings of European artists Essayadi replaces the bright colors nudity and luxury of Orientalist paintings with monochrome settings fully clothed women and strings of Arabic letters taking back ownership of their representation This thought provoking exhibit is sure to keep art lovers excited Inspired by the East is open NOW through January at The British Museum in London Image Lalla Essaydi Bullets chromogenic print mounted to aluminum with a UV protective laminate x inches InspiredByTheEast Photography Art WomenInTheArts thCenturyArt Orientalism islamicart middleeasternart lallaessaydi painting Frieze ArtFairs London BritishMuseum

text: Fascinating Rhythm Painted by Eric Bowman Born in Pasadena and grew up in Orange County CA Oil on canvas x in Essentially a self taught artist Eric had a knack for drawing as far back as he can remember always the class artist throughout his elementary and high school years Early on various art related jobs such as silk screen T shirt printer or surfboard airbrush technician led to a lengthy and successful career as a commercial artist eventually transitioning to fine art painting Eric s style of painting is a mixture of Impressionism and Realism His stylistic influences are the Russian Impressionists and various American Impressionists of the last century He is equally adept at both landscape and figurative painting Light and shadow play a crucial role in solidifying his compositions He has garnered many awards in juried competitions showing in national and regional exhibitions in some of the country s most prestigious galleries and museums His paintings are in collections around the world including England Australia Canada and Mexico Eric resides in northwest Oregon with his wife and daughter museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting rhythm music jazz party ericbowman pasadena orangecounty yourarttimes

text: Dr Peuramaki Brown spent Friday morning at the British Museum Anthropology Library and Archives Study Room examining reports and personal correspondence related to the T A Joyce expedition to the Pearce sites of the Cockscomb Basin Along with the papers were two newly recovered expedition maps of the area and the smaller Williams Ruins site which had been previously misplaced in the archives as well as a modified map of the Maya region with additions updates made by Alfred Maudslay to the Sittee River and South Stann Creek areas These documents are helping us tie our recent reconnaissance trip to the Pearce sites in with previous research in the area as well as our newly acquired lidar data of the area and future plans for investigations Many thanks to Francesca Hillier and Jim Hamill of the BM for their ongoing support scraparky britishmuseum

text: Repost britishmuseum get repost This colourful cloisonn jar was made in th century China The enamel decoration shows a vigorous looking dragon chasing a pearl through clouds Brightly coloured enamelled objects like this were once thought to be vulgar and garish but by the early s they were considered suitable for the emperor s palace the reign mark suggests this jar was used in the Imperial Household In Room you can learn more about the fascinating history of China from BC to the present BritishMuseum China ChineseHistory cloisonn art design London Museum Ming

text: Details from contemporary artworks by Raeda Saadeh and Layla Essaydi at the closing section of the British Museum s wonderful show Inspired by the East how the Islamic world influenced western art The exhibition begins with artworks dated back to the s including ceramics glass jewellery manuscripts as well as painting and drawings The contemporary photographic works by middle eastern and North African women artists are a contemporary reaction to the images of Orientalist representations of the East subverting and undermining works by earlier European and North American artists Exhibition is on til January womenphotographers phototgraphy britishmuseum exhibition

text: Sumerian votive figures from the Abu temple at Eshnunna modern Tell Asmar Iraq to BCE Votive figures such as these are displayed in the Iraq Museum the Louvre the Met Museum and the British Museum among others It is thought that the purpose of votive statues was to offer constant prayers on behalf of the donor owner The most striking feature of such statuettes is the disproportionate size of the eyes Scholars have offered various explanations for this such as the alertness needed for constant prayer or eyes wide open in awe and wonder and eyes as windows to the soul but of course no one knows for certain I absolutely love these little statues and it was a real joy to render them in illustrative form sumeria sumerian babylonian tellasmar akkadian ancientneareast illustration artsandcrafts colour votivefigures iraq ancienthistory sculptures britishmuseum louvre metmuseum iraqmuseum pergamon eshnunna assyria assyrian

text: The British Museum in the Bloomsbury area of London United Kingdom is a public institution dedicated to human history art and culture Its permanent collection of some eight million works is among the largest and most comprehensive in existence having been widely sourced during the era of the British Empire It documents the story of human culture from its beginnings to the present It was the first public national museum in the world The British Museum was established in largely based on the collections of the Irish physician and scientist Sir Hans Sloane It first opened to the public in in Montagu House on the site of the current building Its expansion over the following years was largely a result of expanding British colonisation and has resulted in the creation of several branch institutions the first being the Natural History Museum in London the capital of England and the United Kingdom is a st century city with history stretching back to Roman times At its centre stand the imposing Houses of Parliament the iconic Big Ben clock tower and Westminster Abbey site of British monarch coronations Across the Thames River the London Eye observation wheel provides panoramic views of the South Bank cultural complex and the entire city Standing on the River Thames in the south east of England at the head of its mile km estuary leading to the North Sea London has been a major settlement for two millennia Londinium was founded by the Romans The City of London London s ancient core an area of just square miles km and colloquially known as the Square Mile retains boundaries that follow closely its medieval Info Wikipedia vacations moments travel instatravel ig photooftheday fun ig travel travelblogger travelling travelphotography ig shots travelgram photography throwback instadaily lovelondon travel travelholic instamoments igers instatravel city visitlondon antiquity museum london britishmuseum uk

text: Portrait of a young woman in profile probably the painter Anna Ancher c Painted by Peder Severin Kr yer Born July Stavanger Norway Died November Skagen Denmark Oil on canvas x cm One of the foremost Impressionist painters from Denmark the artist Peder Severin Kroyer was born in Norway but brought up in Copenhagen where he studied at the Royal Academy He became the leading member of the Skagen artist colony a group known as the painters of light This group which included Holger Drachmann and Carl Locher was strongly influenced by French Impressionism In particular they sought to study and capture the effects of light at different times of the day Kroyer s paintings from Skagen are lively and naturalistic and were executed en plein air The influence of Renoir and Whistler can be seen in his paintings Hip Hip Hurrah Kroyer travelled widely spending time in Paris studying the Impressionists particularly Edouard Manet Pierre Auguste Renoir Camille Pissarro Paul Cezanne and Georges Seurat Kroyer was impressed with the art movement and its enthusiasm for painting from real life whether it was a portrait landscape or cityscape It encouraged him to keep his palette light and to loosen his brushstroke Kroyer is best known for his carefree pictures of life in Skagen His wife became his favourite model and from the s she is represented in many of his works Kroyer was a champion of plein air painting and there are black and white photographs of the artist sitting on the beach working on his large canvases The French Impressionists had popularised this artistic practice and it allowed the artist to capture light directly as he saw it The economy of objects in Kroyer s paintings and the priority he gives to atmosphere lends an air of Symbolism to his work text: SWIPE LEFT ON IMAGE ABOVE FOR MORE PICTURES Shaghayegh Cyrous shaghayeghcyrous is an Iranian American artist and curator based in San Francisco She started her art practice in Tehran Iran where she began her artistic practice with urban installation performance and photography Since and moving to the bay area and experiencing life from the lens of a refugee her work has dealt with the experience of cross cultural communication and translation addressing predicaments of estrangement and distance caused by political and cultural power dynamics Her projects incorporate interactive time based strategies such as social practice socially engaged art and participatory performances as well as digital technologies such as video installation and live video chats to create poetic spaces and opportunities for human connection As she continues to research different strategies and languages of navigating various political and cultural issues her practice has extended beyond her art into the curatorial realm Her current focus is on the compression of time and space resulting from digital technologies such as Skype Line and Telegram These technologies enable her and others like her to connect live to their home countries reflecting the desires of exiles and immigrants for communication with homelands that exist beyond their present times and locations Her most recent work explores how digital media plays this critical role in the lives of exiles and immigrants forcing them to navigate two different spaces the physical and the virtual Cyrous holds a BA in Visual Art from For Science and Culture University of Tehran and an MFA in Social Practice from California College of the Arts She recently received Bangkit Arise international art residency of Asian Art Museum and Clarion Alley Mural Project and performed at North x North Festival at Anchorage Museum READ REMAINDER OF BIO IN COMMENTS SECTIONS BELOW

text: Carrying on October s witchcraft and magical theme Two objects of talismanic purpose this time from the newly built Islamic galleries in the British Museum Both of these objects come from Palestine and date to the early th century The first is a necklace that has cobalt blue and white beads used to avert the evil eye which is a curse unknowingly given from the glare of one who is deeply envious This necklace would have been worn by a child or mother as the chunks of alum salt crystals were thought to protect children help stop bleeding and safeguard against fire The red triangular pendant at the bottom contains folded paper written with protective verses from the Quran and the small tortoise shell is a good luck charm to ensure a long and happy life The second object is a baby s bonnet with more blue beads some encasing more alum crystals and another paper of protective verses folded into a triangle Evil eye talismans are ubiquitous now and at least in the west are seen as something one might buy as a tourist in a market in Istanbul However the belief in the evil eye is still held in parts of Asia and the concept of the evil eye has lasted for centuries in both pagan and monotheistic religions perhaps originating in Ancient Greece palestine evileye islamichistory britishmuseum thebritishmuseum talisman handoffatima palestinian islamicart materialculture

text: I molossi nel realismo ellenistico molte sculture di animali in bronzo di questo periodo ci sono note solo attraverso copie di marmo romane I Molossi abitavano nell antico Epiro ed erano imparentati con il moderno mastino e si narra che erano notoriamente feroci Usati sia per guardia agli animali sia per uso domestico a guardia delle propriet e sicurezza nelle citt Aristofane nel V secolo parla dei rischi di tentare di superare una porta sorvegliata da un cane molosso mentre la leggenda narra che il famigerato statista ateniese e generale Alcibiade ne abbia tenuto uno con una coda ancorata Questo cane una volta indossava un colletto Le mascelle spalancate mostrano denti potenti ma la posa rilassata e lo sguardo verso l alto gli conferiscono un aria obbediente Altre cinque versioni di questa scultura tutte trovate vicino a Roma sono ritenute copie romane di un originale in bronzo greco perduto probabilmente del II secolo a C

text: Sunset at Sea c Painted by Thomas Moran Born February Bolton Lancashire England Died August Santa Barbara California United States aged Oil on canvas x cm Moran s family came to American in they made several family members become artists including Peter Edward and Thomas the youngest Moran took an apprenticeship as an engraver at Scattergood Tefler concentrated on refining his own technique in watercolor studying under James Hamilton Hamilton introduced Thomas to the work of J M W Turner whose painterly style remained a major influence throughout Moran s career By the mid s Moran was already exhibiting sophisticated and accomplished paintings Upon marrying Scottish born etcher and landscape painter Mary Nimmo Moran relocated his family to New York where he was hired as an illustrator at Scribner s Monthly This appointment proved to be significant as he was soon promoted to the position of chief illustrator a move that set him on course to become one of the country s most important landscape artists Thomas Moran s name is closely associated with the creation of Yellowstone National Park In the artist was invited by Dr Ferdinand Hayden director of the United States Geological Survey to join his expedition team headed for the Yellowstone region For days Moran painted and sketched over different sites in the region which in tandem with the remarkable photographs of his expedition colleague William H Jackson proved beyond doubt the true majesty of the area s natural beauty Their collective work was undeniably instrumental in influencing Congress to elevate and preserve the Yellowstone expanse making it a national park in At the conclusion of the Hayden Survey Moran continued his work both as a landscape artist and commercial illustrator He entered a successful business relationship with the Santa Fe Railroad which commissioned him to produce paintings of the Grand Canyon for its own marketing purposes The paintings were made into magnificent color lithographs which served to introduce tourists to the beauty of the west

text: Klang day RoyalKlangHeritageWalk walking tour focusing on Klang the RoyalTown of Selangor Whilst most of us thought Parameswara s Melaka years ago as the beginning of Malaysia Klang actually existed years ago with human settlement since prehistoric times Bronze Age drums axes and other artefacts have been found here A bronze bell dating nd century BC was also found here and is now in the BritishMuseum Also found are iron tools called TulangMawas ape bones Klang was mentioned in th century literary works Nagarakretagama dates to the Majapahit Empire Klang River was marked and named on the earliest maritime charts of Admiral ChengHo on his visits to Malacca Klang was under the control of the Malaccan Sultanate in the th century Klang became a producer of tin In the th century the Bugis from Celebes Island Sulawesi began to settle in the coastal region of Selangor including Klang Linggi and Kuala Selangor Being among the finest navigators of SouthEastAsia excellent traders and great warriors who fought using chain mail armoury and used warships in sea battles soon gained political influence becoming feared protectors of the Straits and establishing the Temenggung rule

text: Finding Hamish at the BritishMuseum This is the chess set described in TheWorldOfAllSouls Chess Set twelfth century Cadzow Lodge Scotland Chess set of pieces carved out of walrus ivory and ebony Size ranges from centimeters to centimeters depending on the piece Background Shortly after he first met Diana at Oxford Matthew visited his best friend Hamish Osborne at his hunting lodge in Lanarkshire He was craving Diana and needed to talk While circling the subject of Diana the two played billiards then chess on a large ancient chessboard with carved ivory and ebony pieces that Matthew had given to Hamish Hamish s chess set is similar to the famed Lewis chessmen a set from the twelfth century that was discovered in Scotland in the nineteenth century Most of the pieces are now at the British Museum in London with eleven others at the National Museum of Scotland in Edinburgh The figures look comically glum to the modern eye but scholars believe their expressions were intended to convey strength and wisdom When Gallowglass was downsizing he gave the set to Matthew for safekeeping Later when Matthew was looking for a special gift for Hamish s new house Gallowglass suggested he give him that old set of mine that s gathering dust in the Old Lodge Chess Set twelfth century Cadzow Lodge Scotland Chess set of pieces carved out of walrus ivory and ebony Size ranges text: Fourth century Buddhist terracotta heads probably hacked off by the Taliban and found stuffed in poorly made wooden crates at Heathrow are to be returned to Afghanistan where they will be star museum exhibits Nine sculptural heads and a torso were intercepted at Heathrow in after a flight from Peshawar in Pakistan After a long legal process they were sent to the British Museum last year to be analysed conserved and catalogued A senior curator at the museum said the heads would have been painted and had bodies and would have adorned the walls of Buddhist monasteries in the ancient kingdom of Gandhara about years ago now displayed for a short time at the BM buddhism buddha gandhara britishmuseum

text: Per i nostri anni di matrimonio vincedelgiudice mi ha fatto una fantastica sorpresa mi ha portato giorni a Londra Londra una citt ordinata pulita e organizzata qualche difetto lo ha anche lei Abbiamo visitato i posti pi importanti di interesse della citt tra cui il britishmuseum Un museo che desideravo molto visitare vista la sua grande fama Ci tenevo in particolare vedere i resti e monumenti dell Antico Egitto e antica Grecia Al museo mi ha affascinato particolarmente anche la cultura Assira e il loro modo di incutere timore ai potenziali visitatori della citt e saccheggiatori davvero geniali Ho apprezzato molto le due chiese una dedicata a Santa Maria Maddalena matrona dell Arcipelago dove sono nata Nel suo insieme Londra una citt vivibile e multiculturale dove cultura e storia si intersecano e rendono la citt moderna Per il resto ringrazio Vince per questa fantastica sorpresa e per avermi portato nella citt che desideravo vedere da pi di anni londra anniversariomatrimonio london goodanniversary britishmuseum backingampalace

text: In this hand coloured mezzotint from a country fellow cannot understand why the woman he s infatuated with would instead fall for the strapping sailor The sailor gives the young lady a blue ribbon as the symbol of his affection as the couple is chaperoned by an older woman who s making sure the couple s declarations of love do not go too far The funniest detail however is the dog vomiting into a barrel Suppose he s not much of a romantic The title of this Carington Bowles published piece is The Sailor s Present or The Jealous Clown Image The Trustees of the British Museum prints mezzotint satire humour romance eighteenthcentury thcentury thcenturyart art arthistory britishmuseum
